<TITLE>How Conservatives Can Win The Coming Medicaid Debate -- PFF</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>How Conservatives Can Win The Coming Medicaid Debate</h2>
given by:

Richard Teske <br>
Vice President for External Affairs<br>
Progress and Freedom Foundation<p>

at the<p>

Heritage Foundation's Resource Bank Conference<br>
Chicago, Illinois<br>
April 25, 1996<p>

<P>
<h2>

</h2>

<P>
<blockquote>






I would first like to thank Mitch Pearlstien for his generous introduction.  <p>

I would also like to thank Mitch and Robert Rector for mentioning Marvin
Olasky.  Marvin is a senior fellow at Progress & Freedom Foundation.  We have
just completed publishing his new book with Free Press called Renewing
American Compassion.  It will be available in a store near you after May 7th.<p>

This is the end of the commercial announcement.<p>

To be the fourth speaker in the late afternoon, before a conservative
audience speaking on Medicaid before the cocktail hour is a difficult
assignment.<p>

One suspects that anyone interested in these subjects must be a liberal, but I
submit to you that these very issues are the ultimate test of our political
philosophy.<p>

I come from a genetic Republican family; My grandfather was so conservative he
believed Roosevelt ruined the country..but he meant Teddy!<p>

You have heard I do health care consulting at Greenberg Traurig and am a
vice-president for External Affairs at Progress & Freedom Foundation.<p>

I've worked in health care public policy for over twenty years<p>

But my first experience was in 9th grade when my debate topic was "Should we
Nationalize Health Care"<p>

If I'm able to fight this issue for twenty more years I can retire.<p>

The Progress & Freedom Foundation is a conservative think tank with a twist:
 we are not dedicated to reforming the liberal welfare state.  We are
dedicated to replacing it!  Based upon Traditional American Values as we
enter the information age.<p>

And it is this very information age that is driving the force of
devolution: the subject of this years Heritage Resource Bank Conference..<p>

The previous three speakers have done an excellent job describing the present
Medicaid and welfare programs.<p>

We all know that the Congressional Leadership is just now deciding on its
welfare and Medicaid strategy.<p>

The Medicaid plan, based upon the Governor's proposal, has been drafted.<p>

The key questions remaining between the administration and Republican
Leadership are:<p>
<ol>
<li>If medicaid remains an entitlement or is block granted
<li>If benefits remain defined at federal level
<li>If states will be responsible for paying for the program's called
"umbrella" provisions
</ul><p>
Powerful interests are arrayed against reform or replacement.<p>

If we reprise our tactics from last year's Medicare debate we will be "school
lunched" again.  It will be the political equivalent of Picketts Charge at
Gettysburg.  After failing to turn the Democrats flank we decide to charge up
the middle at their strength!  The same result for Pickett at Gettysburg will
be repeated by Republicans in the fall election.<p>

What I want to talk about in my remaining time is how conservatives can win
on the Medicaid issue, not only politically but most importantly for the
people we intend to serve.<p>

A Basic Truism:<p>

In what is called the caring professions, compassion will trump a balanced
budget every time.<p>

The issue shouldn't be a balanced budget when it comes to Medicare, Medicaid
and Welfare, but it should be the role of government.<p>

And what should that role be?<p>

As our first Republican President Abraham Lincoln said 'To help those who
can't help themselves.'<p>

To win we need to learn and change the language of the debate.<p>

I wish to make three brief points and then await your questions.<p>

I.  First Question:  Who is in the Medicaid program?<p>
<ul>
<li>70% are mothers and children through AFDC  program.
<li>In 1965 Medicaid was an afterthought it has grown like topsy ever since.
 The reason is 70% of costs are not for AFDC mothers and children but for
nursing homes, primarily elderly and primarily female.
<li>Medicaid is a welfare program, but we should think health care when talking
about it.
<li>When I worked for a corporation, people who talked about "consumers" were
liberals;  People who talked about "customers" were conservatives.  You knew
who they were by the language they used.
<li>It is the same in Medicaid: welfare workers talk of "caseloads" and Liberals
talk of consumers.
<li>When I see my mother-in-law in her nursing home she isn't a "caseload" or a
"consumer," she's a patient!
<li>So the answer to the first question: Who is in the program? Is Patients.
<li>"Consumers" look for bargains, "Patients" look for quality health care.
<li>Let us look at the issue politically  There is a gender gap: women are
voting 15-20% more Democratic than men.  There is also a generation gap: 18-29
women vote almost the same as men.  But as you go up the age scale to those
over 65 these women are voting 35% more Democratic than men!
</ul><p>
Something Democrats know and Republicans don't:  'If Bill Clinton is
re-elected Grandmothers will make the difference.'<p>

Democratic ads play on these fears:  That "Grandma" is coming home from the
nursing home because of Republican budget cuts.<p>

We don't have to emulate Bill Clinton by cynically pandering to the special
interests that make up his political coalition.<p>

Rather we must remember what the health care and Medicaid debate are all
about:  helping patients.<p>

It's not about hospitals, doctors, providers, patient pressure groups or
trial lawyers.  We must remember:  if the patient wins then we can't lose!<p>

If, at the end of day, the health care of the Medicaid patient hasn't
improved, then we've failed!<p>

II.  Second Question:  What is the key measurement that should dominate all
others?<p>
<ul>
<li>When I joined HCFA my deputy was a career official from the Daly machine in
Chicago He was one of the three people chosen by Lyndon Johnson to put the
Medicaid program together.
<li>I asked him, "how do you determine what's important?"
<li>He responded, halfway joking "ask yourself four questions:  who wins, who
loses, how much does it cost and who cares."  Mayor Daly would have been
proud.  In health care, we talk about cost, quality and access.
<li>If you change one of these elements you change the other two.
<li>In the old Soviet System:  To preserve egalitarian access, and with little
money, they had poor quality care.
<li>In European socialist countries:  They wanted high quality, but to control
cost they had to ration access to care.
<li>In the US:  we want high quality and universal access, thus costs
skyrocketed.
<li>Medicare and Medicaid: costs are increasing at 10% per year They are the
federal governments fastest growing programs.  If Medicaid was returned to
the states it would constitute up to 40% of the entire state budget. The
Medicaid and Medicare programs rival the Defense Department in size.
<li>Liberals emphasize access and the uninsured, but poor and the uninsured
have universal access: they use hospital emergency rooms!
<li>The question is not access, but who pays for them and where they get care!
<li>Conservatives emphasize costs and it reinforces our Ebenezer Scrooge image.
<li>Look at the marketplace for solutions.  Take advantage of its
lessons: private health insurance costs are trending down.
</ul><p>

We must take advantage of four marketplace trends if we want to change
Medicaid:<p>
<ol>
<li> Devolution vs. Centralization:  Shown by the trend to provide care at the
most cost-effective site-be it a hospital, SNF or at home.
<li> Prevention vs. Acute Care:  Prevention is cost-effective and it provides
better care.
<li> Capitation vs. Fee for Service:  Capitation provides incentives for cost
-effective behavior. It means providers concentrate on competing on the basis
of quality not maximizing re-imbursement.
<li> Distributive vs. "One Size Fits All":  This stresses the benefits of
Medical Innovation and Technology rather than assuring that everyone gets the
same,-albeit mediocre, care
</ol><p>
Thus the answer to the second question:  What is very measure that drives all
others?<p>
<ul>
<li>It is not cost nor access, but quality!
<li>The poor have access, not in right place, maybe in emergency rooms, but they
do have access.
<li>Costs can be controlled in capitated or HMO systems.
<li>Therefore the key is quality:  "We need a single instrument to measure
quality of care to patients regardless of the site where the care is given.
</ul><p>

III.  Third Question:  What is the one policy element that conservatives have
and liberals don't?<p>
<ul>
<li>Of my deputy at HCFA I asked:  "How do you solve all these problems?"
<li>He answered "no matter what the problem, there are only three solutions!:
 Changes in eligibility, reimbursement or coverage."
<li>Eligibility, reimbursement and coverage are the three bureaucratic policy
elements that correspond to access, cost and quality
<li>My deputy was right, in a bureaucratic, top down, one size fits all, command
and control system you can only change these three things.
<li>But in the 1980s, we conservatives were permitted only to change one
element while trying to reform Medicaid.
<li>Liberals refused to limit eligibility: in Medicaid, thanks to Henry Waxman,
they actually greatly expanded it!
<li>Liberals also refused to limit coverage in Medicaid, thanks to Henry
Waxman, benefits were never touched and often expanded.
<li>But because liberals think all providers, like doctors, hospitals,
administrators and manufacturers are Republicans, they gladly permitted us to
cut reimbursement.
<li>This is why at Progress & Freedom we stress replacement not reform.  Reform
did not work in the 80's.
<li>Reform models leave us with the tyranny of the three elements: eligibility,
reimbursement and coverage.
<li>So what is the conservative fourth element?
<li>A clue:  The debate on Medical Savings Accounts.
<li>The reason liberals oppose MSA's as one liberal Congressman recently said:
"The poor will not choose to spend their money on health care, but keep it!"
<li>In other words: we can't trust the poor to do the right thing!  We need a
bureaucrat to tell them.  The poor can't be trusted to choose correctly.
</ul><p>

Well I have some news for our liberal friends:<p>

Poverty is not a mental handicap but an economic condition.<p>

The poor are capable of choosing and that's the answer to the third Question
that terrifies liberals:<p>
The fourth public policy element conservatives have is choice.<p>

Choice: It may define the single most important difference between liberals
and conservatives.<p>
<ul>
<li>We believe in markets, they believe in bureaucracy and bureaucracy is
incompatible with choice.
<li>Don't accept the argument that the marketplace doesn't work in health care.
<li>If you believe this, that means choice doesn't work;  and you must rely on
changes in eligibility, coverage or re-imbursement. You must rely on a
regulatory system to "fix" the market.
<li>When any conservative hears the phrase "Fix the market" their skin should
crawl.
<li>You now have the three words that will change the language of the debate:
<li>Talk of Patients not consumers
<li>Talk of Quality, not costs or access
<li>Talk of Choice, not eligibility, coverage or reimbursement.

<li>Patients, Quality and Choice are the high ground of the debate.
<li>Their focus is consistent with where the private sector is heading. 
<li>They are the basis for a replacement not a reform model for Medicaid.
<li>They will enable not only conservatives to win, but more importantly "we
will truly help those who can't help themselves."
</ul><p>
Thank You.<p>


<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
