<head><title>NRCC Response to SoTU -- Town Hall</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<center>
<h2>Statement by<br>
 National Republican Congressional Committee Chariman<br>
 Bill Paxon</h2>
January 23, 1996
</center>
Contact:  Craig Veith 202.479.7070<P>

<blockquote>
National Republican Congressional Committee Chairman Bill Paxon (R-
NY) made the following statement tonight regarding Bill Clinton's State 
of the Union address.
<P>
"Tonight Bill Clinton proved one thing beyond the shadow of a doubt -- 
he's a congenital liberal who believes that a bigger, more intrusive 
government is the answer to what ails the nation.  Nothing could be 
further from the truth.  
<P>
''Bill Clinton gave a speech that was designed to make people feel good -- 
that's what he does best: make promises to make people like him, then 
break the faith with the American people. 
<P>
"The Republican-controlled 104th Congress is different. We have 
advanced an agenda that is in line with the values and priorities of the 
American people -- balancing the out-of-control federal budget, saving, 
and strengthening Medicare, providing real reform to a failed welfare 
system and giving over-taxed working families much needed tax relief.
<P>
"Bill Clinton and Congressional Democrats should face the facts: 
Republicans are fighting for Americans, young and old.  Democrats are 
fighting for nothing more than re-election.
<P>
"In 1992, Clinton and the Congressional Democrats campaigned for 
change.  In 1994, the voters saw the truth -- Democrats were fighting for 
the failed status quo and they elected a Republican majority to Congress.  
Today, Leon Panetta said this debate is about competing visions for the 
future of America. Republicans want a government that performs better, 
spends less and is less intrusive in the daily lives of every-day Americans.  
Bill Clinton and the Democrats in Congress want a bigger government 
that spends more, taxes more all to fund the failed policies of the status 
quo in Washington.
<P>
"In 1994, the voters said Republicans had a better idea. In 1996, they will 
vote to increase our majority to work with a Republican president so that 
we are able to continue the changes we began in January 1995."
<P>
Many American parents were offended by the "challenge" from the 
President to cherish their children.  Parents don't need the President to tell 
them to love their children and be their "firth teachers."
<P>
The first step toward meeting America's challenges is for Bill Clinton to 
do his part, to transform the "say anything, but do nothing" presidency 
into one that fulfills its responsibilities.  Republicans challenge Bill 
Clinton to do his part by keeping his campaign promises and start telling 
the truth about Medicare. We challenge him to balance the budget, 
provide tax relief for families and for economic growth, and genuinely 
reform welfare. We challenge him to stop trying to scare senior citizens 
about Medicare and act to preserve it for the next generation. The 
Republican Congress already has done the hard work. They already 
consulted the American people for the best solutions, turned them into 
legislation and passed it. All Clinton has to do is put down his veto pen 
and fulfill his campaign promises by using his pen to sign the Republican 
balanced budget into law.
</blockquote>
<P><P>
