<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Lisa Brownlee works in Discovery's <A HREF="hightech.html">High
Technology &amp; Public Policy</A> program and is an attorney (member, Washington
State Bar) practicing with the law firm of Trenite Van Doorne, in Amsterdam,
the Netherlands. Formerly an attorney with Foster, Pepper and Shefelman,
Seattle, she resigned in 1993 to pursue a fellowship with the Max Planck
Institute for Foreign and International Patent, Copyright and Competition
Law in Munich, Germany.<BR>
<BR>
Brownlee joined Trenite Van Doorne in 1994, where her practice includes
US and international copyrights and licensing, US and Benelux trademark
matters, and European Union intellectual property and competition law matters.<BR>
<BR>
She has recently authored several publications on intellectual property
law, including a Discovery Institute Inquiry <A HREF="browninq.html"><B><I>Is
the European Union promoting a protectionist agenda against the global Internet?</I></B>
</A>and <I>&quot;Recent Changes in the Duration of Copyright in the United
States and Europe:Procedure &amp; Policy</I> published in the <I>Fordham
Intellectual Property, Media &amp; Entertainment Law Journal</I>.. Brownlee
is often published in the National Law Journal, West's Washington Practice,
and Puget Sound Business Journal.<BR>
