<head>
<title>Congressional Testimony before the Subcommittee on Telecommunications and Finance & Energy and Power Committees -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<h2>Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 [PUHCA]</h2><br>
<h3>Before the Subcommittee on Telecommunications and Finance
and Subcommittee on Energy and Power Committee on Commerce</h3>
</center>
<b>Statement of Thomas M. Lenard<br>
Senior Fellow and Director of Regulatory Studies, The Progress & Freedom Foundation</b><p>
August 4, 1995
<p>
<br>
The Security and Exchange Commissions report, The Regulation of
Public-Utility Holding Companies, describes a depression-era regulatory
program enacted under vastly different circumstances than exist today.  In
the current marketplace, the benefits from PUHCA are not sufficient to
outweigh the potentially substantial costs.
<p>
Increases in competition in both the electric and gas markets diminish the
need for regulation in general.  But even in the absence of these competitive
pressures, the pervasiveness of other regulatory programs makes the PUHCA
requirements duplicative and unnecessary.  If unchanged, PUHCA will be a
significant impediment to the competitive restructuring of the electric
utility industry in the future.  For the gas industry, which has to a large
extent already been restructured, the PUHCA restrictions may be even more
burdensome
<p>
The social costs of PUHCA restrictions are estimated to be between $3 and
$12.6 billion in present value terms.  The major sources of these costs are
the Acts geographic restrictions on mergers, and its limitations on
diversification into non-utility lines of business.
<p>
Because of these costs, the case for unconditional PUHCA repeal seems
compelling.  There is currently ample regulatory authority without PUHCA to
protect consumers of electricity and natural gas.  At the same time, these
markets are growing more competitive, diminishing the need for regulation. 
<p>
<b> Statement of Thomas M. Lenard</b>
<p>
Chairman Fields, Chairman Schaefer and Members of the Subcommittees.  It is
pleasure have this opportunity to discuss the recent Security and Exchange
Commission (SEC) report on the regulation of public utility holding companies
 and the merits of various options for modifying or repealing the Public
Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 (PUHCA).
<p>
This issue is of great interest to us, in part because The Progress &
Freedom Foundation is in the process of assembling a team of scholars who
will undertake a major project on The Future of Energy Transmission.  The
purpose of this project is to develop an operational model that will provide
the legal structure necessary for a more competitive electricity market,
including a policy agenda aimed at eliminating artificial constraints on the
structure, scope and activities of electric power producers.  While
additional analysis on the promotion of competition may be developed during
the course of our project, enough is known now to conclude that retention of
PUHCA is not in the public interest.  The economic costs of the restrictions
PUHCA imposes on electric and gas holding company activities will only grow
larger as competition increases in this sector of our economy.  Competitive
forces will require market participants to adapt in 
 unpredictable ways.  If unchanged, PUHCA will be a significant impediment to
the competitive restructuring of the electric utility industry in the future.
 For the gas industry, which has to a large extent already been restructured,
the PUHCA restrictions may be even more burdensome. 
<p>
PUHCAs relevance extends to the rapid changes occurring in
telecommunications, an area on which we also have been working.   The
electric utility industry has a large and growing network of fiber optic
cable and appears to be well positioned to compete in telecommunications
markets.  Under PUHCA, however, the participation in these markets by
registered holding companies would be severely limited.   
<p>
The Division of Investment Management of the SEC should be commended for
producing a very informative report on PUHCA and I agree generally with its
conclusions.  The report describes a depression-era regulatory program
enacted under vastly different circumstances than exist today.  In the
current marketplace, the benefits from PUHCA are not sufficient to outweigh
the potentially substantial costs.
<p>
PUHCA was enacted in order to address a public-utility holding company
structure believed to concentrate control of vast utility empires in a few
hands, which led to deception of investors, excessive rates for consumers,
and obstruction of state utility regulation.   In order to address these
purported problems, the Act required the integration and simplification of
holding company systems into single integrated public-utility systems, a
process largely completed by 1952.  Currently, registered holding companies
require SEC approval to issue or sell securities, acquire utility or
nonutility assets, sell utility assets or enter into service arrangements
with sister companies.  
<p>
Both the structure of the utility industry itself and the other regulatory
programs to which it is subject have changed dramatically since 1935.  At the
time PUHCA was enacted, its rules applied to over 200 registered utility
companies, a large share of the utility industry.   In 1932, for example,
three holding companies accounted for about half of the investor-owned
electric utility market.  Today, only 14 active holding companies remain
registered under the Act.  The 11 registered electric utility holding
companies account for about 20 percent of investor-owned utility retail
electricity sales.  Most of the largest electric utilities and most of the
gas industry are not regulated under the Act, leading to a system that
arbitrarily imposes a stringent set of regulatory requirements on a small
subset of industry for no apparent economic reason.    
 <p>
In recent years, there has been a significant increase in competition in
both the electric and gas markets and this diminishes the need for regulation
in general.  But even in the absence of these competitive pressures, the
pervasiveness of other regulatory programs makes the PUHCA requirements
duplicative and unnecessary:
<p>
The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) is responsible for
regulating rates for the interstate wholesale electricity and natural gas
markets.   FERC also has the authority to review in advance mergers and
securities issuances.  As part of its regulatory functions, FERC collects
detailed financial information and has established uniform systems of
accounts to which regulated utilities must adhere. 
<p>
State regulators also have expanded their authority over both electric and
gas utilities.   States regulate securities issuances, acquisition and
diversification activities and prescribe uniform systems of accounts for
regulatory purposes.
<p>
The SEC itself regulates public-utility holding companies as it does all
other issuers of securities, requiring disclosure of comprehensive financial
data in a standardized form. 
<p>
The Department of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission have the
authority to challenge utility mergers they deem to be anticompetitive.
<p>
Finally, and importantly, the market itself demands a level of disclosure
unheard of in the days when PUHCA was passed into law for any company that
wants to attract outside capital. 
<p>
The SEC Reports chapter on legislative recommendations goes into
considerable detail concerning why PUHCAs provisions are both unnecessary
and harmful.   A study by Carpenter and Graves estimated the social costs of
PUHCA restrictions to be between $3 and $12.6 billion in present value terms.
<p>
The major sources of these costs are the Acts geographic restrictions on
mergers with utilities in non-contiguous areas, which preclude the
realization of economies associated with overhead expenses and coordination
activities, and the Acts limitations on diversification into non-utility
lines of business. 
<p>    
 With respect to entrance into non-utility activities, Carpenter and Graves
stress the potential benefits of utility entry into cable TV and other
telecommunications services, pointing out that the electric utility industry
already has laid down 10,000 miles of fiber optic cable for its own data
transmission and other purposes, with the vast majority of this cable
capacity being unutilized and available for other purposes.  Many anticipate
that electric utilities will find significant efficiencies in having homes
wired for improved energy-use metering and applications such as real time
pricing of electricity.  In the event this takes place, utilities will
obviously be in a good position to utilize the same wires to offer
telecommunications services at very competitive prices.  Restrictions on the
offer of such services, through PUHCA or otherwise, would clearly be costly
to consumers.  This is only one example of the potential benefits of
diversification.
<p>
For all these reasons, the case for unconditional PUHCA repeal seems quite
compelling.  With respect to access to books and records, utilities generally
have the burden of proof in rate proceedings.  Therefore, as a practical
matter, even when a state commission does not have independent access to the
books and records of a utility affiliate, the utility will be required to
provide such records to the extent that they relate to the recovery of costs.
Similarly, the issue of the reasonableness of affiliate transactions can be
addressed by  FERC and the states through their normal ratemaking
authorities.  
<p>
There is currently ample regulatory authority without PUHCA to protect
consumers of electricity and natural gas.  At the same time, these markets
are growing more competitive, diminishing the need for regulation.  The costs
of retaining PUHCA can be quite significant in terms of foregone
opportunities for realization of economies through acquisition and
diversification and the ability of heavily regulated industries to adapt to a
more competitive environment.  Given the remaining regulatory protections and
the increasingly competitive environment, the risks of PUHCA repeal seem
small.  The SEC has been recommending PUHCA repeal, albeit in slightly
different forms, for over a decade.   It seems time for the Congress to act.
<p>
<center>

</center>
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
