<title>Tax Reform NOW! -- Flat Tax Rate Bibliography</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>[<a href="experts.html">Experts</a>][<a href="welcome.html">Home</a>][<a href="links.html">Links</a>][<a href="http://www.townhall.com">Town Hall</a>]<p>
<img src="tr-now2.gif" width=300 height=90 border=0 alt="Tax Reform NOW! logo">
<br>
<h1><font color="blue">FLAT RATE TAX BIBLIOGRAPHY</font></h1>

Compiled by <a href="mailto:73440.3456@compuserve.com">Bruce Bartlett</a><br>
<a href="http://www.public-policy.org/~ncpa/">National Center for Policy Analysis</a>
<P>
<hr>
<p>

Sources listed alphabetically by author, use <a name="quick">QuickLinks</a> to navigate through alphabet, or scroll through entire document. <p>

[ <a href="#A">A-C</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#D">D-G</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#H">H-K</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#L">L-O</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#P">P-R</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#S">S-V</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#W">W-Z</a> ]
</center>
<p><p>


<hr>
<a name="A"></a>A-C<p>



Aaron, Henry J. 1982.  "Toward Fairer Taxation."  <i>New York Times</i>  (September 26).
<blockquote>
          Opposes pure flat rate tax, but favors rate reduction
          and base-broadening.
</blockquote><p>
Altig, David, and Charles T. Carlstrom. 1994.  "The Efficiency and Welfare Effects of Tax Reform: Are Fewer Brackets Better than More?"  <i>Economic Review</i>, Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, vol. 30, no. 4 (4th Quarter), pp. 30-42.
<blockquote>
          Finds that a pure flat rate tax is preferable to a
          modified flat rate system.
</blockquote><p>
Armey, Richard K. 1994a.  "Review Merits of Flat Tax."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (June 16).
<p>
Armey, Richard K. 1994b.  "The Flat Tax: Restoring Freedom and Fairness."  <i>Commonsense</i> (Fall), pp. 48-54.
<p>
Auerbach, Alan J., Laurence Kotlikoff, and Jonathan Skinner. 1983.  "The Efficiency Gains from Dynamic Tax Reform."  <i>International Economic Review</i>, vol. 24, no. 1 (February), pp. 81-100.
<blockquote>
          Finds large efficiency gains from switching to a
          proportional, consumption-based tax system.  Also finds
          large efficiency costs from even small degrees of
          progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
Ballard, Charles L., John B. Shoven, and John Whalley. 1985a.  "General Equilibrium Computations of the Marginal Welfare Costs of Taxes in the United States."  <i>American Economic
     Review</i>, vol. 75, no. 1 (March), pp. 128-138.
<blockquote>
          Finds that the excess burden of the U.S. tax system is
          as much as 56% of tax revenue.
</blockquote><p>
Ballard, Charles L., John B. Shoven, and John Whalley. 1985b.  "The Total Welfare Cost of the United States Tax System: A General Equilibrium Approach." <i>National Tax Journal</i>, vol.
     38, no. 2 (June), pp. 125-140.
<blockquote>
          Finds large welfare gains from eliminating distortions
          in the U.S. tax system and replacing it with a
          consumption-based system.
</blockquote><p>
Bankman, Joseph, and Thomas Griffith. 1987.  "Social Welfare and
     the Rate Structure: A New Look at Progressive Taxation." 
     <i>California Law Review</i>, vol. 75, no. 6 (December), pp. 1905-
1967.
<blockquote>
          Two professors of law at the University of Southern
          California support progressivity, but oppose graduated
          tax rates.  They favor achieving redistribution through
          income transfers rather than taxation.
</blockquote><p>
Bartlett, Bruce. 1978.  "The Economics of Progressive Taxation." 
     <i>Modern Age</i>, vol. 22, no. 3 (Summer), pp. 285-292.
<blockquote>
          Presents a comprehensive set of arguments against
          progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
Bartlett, Bruce. 1986.  "Federal Income Tax Reform: Resuming the
     Battle."  <i>Backgrounder</i> No. 554, <a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a>
     (December 30).
<blockquote>
          Favors flat-rate tax and suggests a further effort to
          eliminate so-called tax expenditures in return for
          lower rates.  See also Henderson (1988).
</blockquote><p>
Bartlett, Bruce. 1995a.  "Don't Cut Taxes--Flatten Them." 
    <i>Fortune</i> (April 17), p. 215.
<p>
Bartlett, Bruce. 1995b.  "Will the Flat Tax KO Housing?"  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (August 2).
<blockquote>
          Argues that elimination of mortgage interest
          deductibility as part of tax reform would not harm
          housing.
</blockquote><p>
Beaudry, Robert V. 1984.  "The Flat Rate Tax: Is It a Viable Solution to the Crisis Facing the Internal Revenue Code?"  <i>Oklahoma City University Law Review</i>, vol. 9, no. 2 (Summer),
     pp. 219-270.
<blockquote>
          Believes that the flat rate tax creates as many
          problems as it solves, and that the major problems of
          the tax system can be fixed without overhauling the
          entire tax code.
</blockquote><p>
Berger, Curtis J. 1985.  "In Behalf of a Single-Rate Flat Tax." 
    <i> Saint Louis University Law Journal</i>, vol. 29, no. 4 (June),
     pp. 993-1027.
<blockquote>
          Favors a flat-rate tax to replace both the individual
          income tax and the payroll tax.
</blockquote><p>
Berry, John M. 1982.  "Flat-Rate Taxation Gains Momentum Among Reformers."  <i>Washington Post</i> (July 4), pp. F1, F4.
<p>
Bickley, James M., and Gregg A. Eisenwein. 1995.  "An Overview of
     Current Flat Rate Tax Proposals." CRS Report for Congress
     No. 95-221E (February 1).
<p>
Blum, Walter J. 1982.  "Revisiting the Uneasy Case for
     Progressive Taxation."  <i>Taxes--The Tax Magazine</i>, vol. 60
     (January), pp. 16-21.
<blockquote>
                    A professor of law at the University of Chicago, who
          had earlier co-authored a book supporting progressive
          taxation (Blum and Kalven, 1953), now believes that
          slower economic growth, high inflation, and the
          expansion of the size of government have undermined the
          argument for progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
Blum, Walter J., and Harry Kalven Jr. 1953.  <i>The Uneasy Case for
     Progressive Taxation</i>.  Chicago: University of Chicago Press.
<blockquote>
          Exhaustive discussion of issues relating to
          progressivity.  While noting powerful arguments against
          progressivity, the authors nevertheless support its
          retention.  For second thoughts by one of the authors
          see Blum (1982).
</blockquote><p>
Blumenthal, Marsha, and Joel Slemrod. 1992.  "The Compliance Cost
     of the U.S. Individual Income Tax System: A Second Look
     After Tax Reform."  <i>National Tax Journal</i>, vol. 45, no. 2
     (June), pp. 185-202.
<blockquote>
          Finds no evidence that the Tax Reform Act of 1986
          reduced the compliance cost of the tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Boaz, David. 1982.  "But Will It Reduce Taxes?"  <i>Inquiry</i>
     (September), p. 31.
<blockquote>
          Says that reducing taxes, not changing the way they are
          collected, is the real issue and that the flat-rate may
          be a red herring, diverting energy away from tax
          reduction.  See also Feder (1982).
</blockquote><p>
Brimelow, Peter. 1981.  "One Tax Bracket?  The Flat-Rate Levy Has
     Gained Widespread Support."  <i>Barron's</i> (August 3), pp. 11,
     21-24.
<blockquote>
          Favors flat-rate tax because it would reduce regulatory
          burden of tax system, improve incentives, reduce
          distortions, increase equity, and end bracket-creep.
</blockquote><p>
Brimelow, Peter. 1982a.  "Get Rid of the Creep: A Single Tax Rate Would Ease the Pain of April 15."  <i>Barron's</i> (April 12),  p. 9.
<p>
Brimelow, Peter. 1982b.  "Hands Off the Flat Tax: It Shouldn't Be
     Used for Raising the Take." <i>Barron's</i> (September 13).
<blockquote>
          Opposes using a flat-rate to increase overall taxation.
</blockquote><p>
Browning, Edgar K. 1976.  "The Marginal Cost of Public Funds."  <i>Journal of Political Economy</i>, vol. 84, no. 2 (April), pp. 283-298.
<blockquote>
                    The total welfare cost of the income tax in 1974 is
          estimated to be $19 billion and the marginal cost
          ranges from 9% to 16% of labor income.
</blockquote><p>
Browning, Edgar K. 1987.  "On the Marginal Welfare Cost of
     Taxation."  <i>American Economic Review</i>, vol. 77, no. 1
     (March), pp. 11-23.
<p>
Browning, Jacquelene M. 1979.  "Estimating the Welfare Cost of Tax Preferences."  <i>Public Finance Quarterly</i>, vol. 7, no. 2  (April), pp. 199-219.
<blockquote>
          Finds that the welfare cost of tax preferences, due to
          their distortion of relative prices, was $8 billion in
          1974, or 6.7% of revenue.
</blockquote><p>
Browning, Edgar K., and Jacquelene M. Browning. 1985.  "Why Not a
     True Flat Rate Tax?"  <i>Cato Journal</i>, vol. 5, no. 2 (Fall),
     pp. 629-650.
<blockquote>
          Two professors of economics at Texas A&M believes that
          the efficiency gains from adoption of a true flat-rate
          tax would be very large, and that these efficiency
          gains would largely offset most of the increased costs
          for low and middle income households.
</blockquote><p>
Buchanan, James M. 1993.  "The Political Efficiency of General Taxation."  <i>National Tax Journal</i>, vol. 46, no. 4 (December),
     401-410.
<blockquote>
          Supports a uniform proportional rate of tax on all
          incomes.
</blockquote><p>
Buchanan, Pat. 1994.  "Armey's Tax War on Washington."  <i>Washington Times</i> (June 27).
<p>
Buckley, William F. 1973.  "Taxation: Toward a Simplified Tax." 
     In <i>Four Reforms: A Guide for the Seventies</i>.  New York: G.P.
     Putnam's Sons, pp. 47-71.
<blockquote>
          Prominent conservative columnist favors a 15% flat-rate
          on individuals as well as abolition of the corporate
          tax.
</blockquote><p>
<a href="/heritage/staff/butler.htm">Butler, Stuart M.</a> 1982.  "Snags in a Flat Tax."  <i>New York Times</i> (September 26).
<blockquote>
          The director of domestic policy studies at <a href="/heritage">The Heritage
          Foundation</a> believes that deduction for charitable
          contributions creates alternatives to government
          programs.  Its elimination could put more pressure on
          government to deal with social problems.
</blockquote><p>
Byrne, John A. 1982.  "The Hong Kong Solution."  <i>Forbes</i> (July 19): 76.
<blockquote>
          Discusses Hong Kong's flat-rate tax system.  See also
          Rabushka (1979) and Chow and Papanek (1981).
</blockquote><p>
Chandler, Clay. 1995. "Flat Tax Proposals Take Center Stage." <i>Washington Post</i> (September 3).
<p>
Chow, Steven C., and Gustav F. Papanek. 1981.  "Laissez-Faire, Growth and Equity--Hong Kong."  <i>The Economic Journal</i>, vol. 91 (June), pp. 466-485.
<blockquote>
          The authors review the impressive experience of Hong
          Kong in achieving high growth and a more equal
          distribution of income.  Since Hong Kong has long had a
          low flat-rate tax system, this provides important
          support for such a tax system.  See also Rabushka
          (1979) and Byrne (1982).
</blockquote><p>
Cicin, Velemir. 1995.  "Flat Tax Conference."  San Diego: A.B. Laffer, V.A. Canto & Associates.
<blockquote>
          Transcript of a conference on the flat rate tax held on
          November 6, 1995.  Speakers include supporters and
          opponents of a flat rate tax.
</blockquote><p>
Clark, Timothy B. 1982.  "Flat-Rate Income Tax Debate May Spur Attacks on Some Tax Breaks."  <i>National Journal</i> (November 13), pp. 1928-1933.
<p>
Coats, Warren L., Jr. 1974.  "The Principles of Tax Reform."  <i>Challenge</i> (January-February), pp. 12-21.
<blockquote>
          Suggests a general set of principles to guide tax
          reform which favor a flat-rate tax on a broader tax
          base.
</blockquote><p>
Cockburn, Alexander, and Robert Pollin. 1992.  "Why the Left Should Support the Flat Tax."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (April 2), p. A15.
<blockquote>
          Two prominent leftists argue in favor of a flat-rate
          tax proposal put forward by former California Governor
          Jerry Brown and attack left-wing critics of his plan. 
          See also Hitchens (1994).
</blockquote><p>
Cohen, Richard E. 1982.  "Government by Gimmickry."  <i>National Journal</i> (July 24), p. 1311.
<blockquote>
          Believes that flat-rate tax is a gimmick like the
          balanced budget amendment, neither of which seriously
          deal with the problems they are designed to address.
</blockquote><p>
Conable, Barber. 1985.  "Why the Flat Tax Will Fall Flat."  <i>Fortune</i> (February 4), pp. 115-116.
<blockquote>
          A longtime former member of the House Ways & Means
          Committee is skeptical of the political chances of
          major tax reform.
</blockquote><p>
Conte, Christopher. 1982.  "Idea of Flat-Rate Tax Is Gaining, but
     Passage Appears to Be Unlikely."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (July
     8).
<p>
Cook, Eric W. 1985.  "Revenue and Distributional Impacts of the Hall-Rabushka Flat Tax Proposal."  <i>Cato Journal</i>, vol. 5, no. 2 (Fall), pp. 477-480.
<blockquote>
          An economist from the Joint Committee on Taxation
          believes that the Hall-Rabushka proposal would not be
          revenue-neutral, as claimed, but would instead reduce
          federal revenues significantly, thus requiring either
          higher rates or a broader tax base to maintain existing
          revenues.
</blockquote><p>
Cowan, Edward. 1982.  "'Flat' Income Tax Gaining Advocates." <i>New
     York Times</i> (May 25), p. D6.
<p>
<a name="D"></a>D-G<p>
<a href="#quick">Back to QuickLinks</a><p>
DeConcini, Dennis. 1982.  "A Flat-Rate Tax." <i>Journal of the Institute for Socioeconomic Studies</i>, vol. 7, no. 3 (Autumn),
     pp. 70-83.
<blockquote>
          A U.S. Senator from Arizona favors a flat-rate tax
          along lines of Hall-Rabushka proposal.
</blockquote><p>
Deloitte & Touche. 1995. <i>Fundamental Tax Reform: An Issues Brief</i>.
     Washington: Deloitte & Touche.
<p>
Dentzer, Susan. 1992.  "Brown's New Fad: A Flat Tax."
     <i>U.S. News & World Report</i> (April 6), pp. 29, 32.
<blockquote>
          Reviews Brown proposal.
</blockquote><p>
Doernberg, Richard L. 1982.  "The Case Against Withholding."  <i>Texas Law Review</i>, vol. 61, no. 4 (December), pp. 595-653.
<blockquote>
          Favors abolition of tax withholding.  (Such a proposal
          has been made by Congressman Richard Armey as part of
          his tax reform proposal.)
</blockquote><p>
Doernberg, Richard L. 1985.  "A Workable Flat Rate Consumption Tax."  <i>Iowa Law Review</i>, vol. 70, no. 2 (January), pp. 425-
485.
<blockquote>
                    A professor of law at Emory reviews the Hall-Rabushka
          proposal.  While finding some defects, believes it
          would be a vast improvement over existing system.
</blockquote><p>
Dunn, Robert. 1995.  "Flat-Tax Fantasies." <i>Washington Post</i> (September 13).
<blockquote>
          Attacks Shelton (1995).
</blockquote><p>
Eisner, Robert. 1995.  "Makes Taxes Fair, Not Flat."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (April 11).
<p>
Entin, Stephen. 1995.  "Treasury Trips Over Flat Tax Facts."  <i>Washington Times</i> (January 4).
<p>
Epstein, Richard A. 1985.  "Taxation."  In <i>Takings: Private Property and the Power of Eminent Domain</i>.  Cambridge: Harvard University Press, pp. 283-305.
<blockquote>
          A professor of law at the University of Chicago argues
          that a flat-rate tax is the only tax system consistent
          with the "benefit" principle, and thus constitutionally
          sound.
</blockquote><p>
Epstein, Richard A. 1986.  "Taxation in a Lockean World."  <i>Social
     Philosophy and Policy</i>, vol. 4, no. 1 (Autumn), pp. 49-74.
<blockquote>
          Argues that in principle people should be taxed exactly
          according to the benefits they receive from government. 
          Since, as a practical matter, it is impossible to
          precisely measure each individual's government
          benefits, a low flat-rate system is a close
          approximation of an ideal tax.
</blockquote><p>
Esenwein, Gregg A. 1982.  "An Overview of the Issues Concerning a
     Flat-Rate Income Tax."  <i>Tax Notes</i> (June 21), pp. 947-951.
<blockquote>
          An economist at the Congressional Research Service
          points out that adoption of a flat-rate tax would not
          necessarily eliminate progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
Farrell, Christopher. 1995.  "A Jumble Only a Flat Tax Can
     Untangle."  <i>Business Week</i> (January 9), p. 39.
<p>
Feder, Don. 1982.  "Flat Tax Warning."  <i>On Principle</i> (November 1), pp. 81-83.
<blockquote>
          Raises concern that many flat-rate tax proposals (e.g.,
          Bradley-Gephardt proposal) may lead to higher taxes.
</blockquote><p>
Fellows, James A. 1983.  "The Rebirth of the Flat-Rate Income Tax."  <i>The Tax Executive</i>, vol. 35 (April), pp. 230-234.
<blockquote>
                    Favors a flat-rate tax, but believes that it is
          unrealistic politically.
</blockquote><p>
Ferguson, Andrew. 1995. "Postcard from Heaven?" <i>Washingtonian</i> (April), pp. 47-49.
<p>
Ferrara, Peter. 1984.  "Flat Tax Conflict?"  <i>Washington Times</i> (February 9).
<blockquote>
          Favors lower tax rates, but believes that many
          deductions are justified and should not be abandoned
          simply to obtain lower rates.
</blockquote><p>
Fessler, Pamela. 1982.  "Flat-Rate Tax Plan Advanced as Radical Cure for Problems of Existing Revenue System." <i>Congressional Quarterly</i> (June 5), pp. 1331-1334.
<p>
Fingleton, Eamonn. 1982.  "The Flat Tax That Isn't."  <i>Forbes</i> (August 2), pp. 36-37.
<blockquote>
          Opposes proposal by Senator Bradley as not a true flat-
rate tax; favors Hall-Rabushka proposal.
</blockquote><p>
Flowers, Marilyn R. 1983.  "A Radical Proposal for Tax Reform." 
<i>Public Policy Notes</i>, University of Oklahoma (Summer), pp. 1-
11.
<blockquote>
          Reviews Hall and Rabushka (1983).
</blockquote><p>
Friedman, Milton. 1962.  "The Distribution of Income."  In
     <i>Capitalism and Freedom</i>.  Chicago: University of Chicago
     Press, pp. 161-176.
<blockquote>
          "All things considered, the personal income tax
          structure that seems to me best is a flat-rate tax on
          income above an exemption, with income defined very
          broadly and deductions allowed only for strictly
          defined expenses of earning income." (p. 174)
</blockquote><p>
Friedman, Milton. 1968.  "Regressive Income Tax."  <i>Newsweek</i> (April 22).  Reprinted in <i>An Economist's Protest</i>.  Glen Ridge, New Jersey: Thomas Horton, 1972, pp. 76-77.
<p>
Friedman, Milton. 1976.  "Tax Reform: An Impossible Dream." <i>Newsweek</i> (April 12), p. 93.
<blockquote>
          Points out that burden of a tax exceeds the revenue
          yield, due to compliances costs, and that a reduction
          in tax rates would lower such costs.
</blockquote><p>
Friedman, Milton. 1980.  "A Simple Tax Reform."  <i>Newsweek</i>
     (August 18), p. 68.
<blockquote>
                    Favors a reduction in the top income tax rate to 25%.
</blockquote><p>
Friedman, Milton. 1982.  "How Flat Is Flat?" <i>Newsweek</i>
     (August 2), p. 52.
<blockquote>
          Believes that adverse impact of a flat-rate tax on poor
          and middle class is exaggerated.  Points out that poor
          would be protected by higher personal exemption. 
          Although some in the middle class would pay more, due
          to curtailment of deductions, others would gain. 
          Favors a constitutional amendment to require flat-rate.
</blockquote><p>
Friedman, Milton. 1995.  "Why a Flat Tax Is Not Politically Feasible."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (March 30).
<blockquote>
          Believes political obstacles to a flat tax are
          insurmountable.
</blockquote><p>
Friedman, Milton, and Rose Friedman. 1984.  "A Flat Tax."  In <i>Tyranny of the Status Quo</i>.  New York: Harcourt Brace
     Jovanovich, pp. 62-67.
<blockquote>
          Believes that a constitutional amendment is necessary
          to achieve a true flat-rate tax.
</blockquote><p>
Galbraith, James K., and Greg Davidson. 1982.  "Flattening the Progressive Tax."  <i>The New Leader</i> (August 9-23).
<blockquote>
          See no real benefits and many disadvantages to flat-
rate tax.  Favor retention of progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
General Accounting Office. 1989.  Economic, Administrative, and Taxpayer Compliance Aspects of a Gross Income Tax.  GAO/GGD-
89-36 (February).
<blockquote>
          Points out that a gross income tax would tax firms
          based solely on gross receipts regardless of profit,
          thus subjecting firms with losses to tax.  It would
          also encourage vertical integration of firms to
          minimize tax.  See also U.S. Treasury Department
          (1986).
</blockquote><p>
Glassman, James K. 1994.  "Praise the Capital Gains Cut and Pass
     the Flat Tax."  <i>Washington Post</i> (November 30).
<p>
Gleckman, Howard. 1992.  "'Jerry's Tax': Wrong Answer, Right Questions."  <i>Business Week</i> (April 13), p. 30.
<blockquote>
          Supports Brown proposal's focus on taxing consumption
          instead of income, but believes that it would be better
          to achieve this goal incrementally.
</blockquote><p>
Good, Jeffrey. 1982.  "Flat Tax Steamrolls Fairness."
    <i> People & Taxes</i> (June), pp. 8-9.
<blockquote>
          Favors lower rates and broader base, but opposes flat-
rate.
</blockquote><p>
Goodgame, Dan. 1996.  "Is This Tax Flat Unfair?"  <i>Time</i> (January 29), pp. 30-31.
<p>
Graetz, Michael J. 1983.  "The 1982 Minimum Tax Amendments as a First Step in the Transition to a "Flat-Rate' Tax." <i>Southern California Law Review</i>, vol. 56 (January), pp. 527-
571.
<blockquote>
          Believes that the minimum tax can be used as a
          transition to a flat-rate tax system.  Similar idea
          suggested in Hall, Hume and Rabushka (1986).
</blockquote><p>
Greenhouse, Steven. 1992.  "Fairness and a Flat Tax."
     <i>New York Times</i> (March 26).
<blockquote>
          Discusses flat rate proposal put forward by former
          California Governor Jerry Brown during 1992 Democratic
          presidential primary.
</blockquote><p>
Gruber, William. 1982.  "Flat Tax Rate Gains Momentum."  <i>Chicago
     Tribune</i> (August 4), sec. 3, pp. 1, 3.
<p>
Guttman, George. 1983.  "The Single-Rate Income Tax: Policy Questions and Technical Issues."  <i>Tax Notes</i> (November 14),
     pp. 539-557.
<blockquote>
          Favors some base broadening combined with modest rate
          reductions, rather than a pure flat-rate tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Gwartney, James, and James Long. 1985.  "Is the Flat Tax a
     Radical Idea?"  <i>Cato Journal</i>, vol. 5, no. 2 (Fall), pp. 407-
432.
<blockquote>
          The authors argue against progressivity on the ground
          that taxable income is a poor measure of economic
          status.  Thus high progressive tax rates fail to
          achieve their egalitarian purpose.  However, in the
          process significant economic disincentives and
          inefficiencies are introduced which reduce growth and
          fairness.  Consequently, a flat-rate may be a
          preferable alternative.
</blockquote><p>
