</blockquote><p>
Rosenbaum, David E. 1995.  "Debate on Flat Tax Revives Simplicity
     vs. Fairness Issue."  <i>New York Times</i> (April 18).
<p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1982a.  "Flat-Rate: The Latest Con." <i>The Libertarian Forum</i> (July), p. 2.
<blockquote>
          Believes that a major motive for flat-rate is envy--
forcing everyone to "pay their fair share."
</blockquote><p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1982b.  "The Flat Rate Trap."  <i>Libertarian Vanguard</i> (August), pp. 1-4.
<blockquote>
          Opposes flat-rate tax because it would eliminate
          deductions which presently protect taxpayers from
          taxation.
</blockquote><p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1982c.  "Flat-Rate Debate."  <i>Reason</i>
     (September), p. 47.
<blockquote>
          Believes that middle class would pay more taxes under
          flat-rate system.
</blockquote><p>
Rothbard, Murray. 1985.  "The Flat Tax: A Skeptical View."  <i>Issues in Economic Policy</i>, Ludwig von Mises Institute.
<blockquote>
          Believes that a flat-rate tax would be neither fairer
          nor more economically sound than existing tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Rowan, Carl T. 1982.  "Don't Buy That Flat-Rate Tax."
     <i>Washington Post</i> (June 25).
<blockquote>
          Strongly opposes a flat-rate tax.
</blockquote><p>
Ruby, Michael. 1995.  "Three Cheers for a Flat Tax!"  <i>U.S. News &
     World Report</i> (February 20), p. 76.
<p>
Rudnick, Rebecca S. 1989.  "Who Should Pay the Corporate Tax in a
     Flat Tax World?"  <i>Case Western Reserve Law Review</i>, vol. 39,
     no. 4, pp. 965-1269.
<p>
<a name="S"></a>S-V<p>
<a href="#quick">Back to QuickLinks</a><p>

Safire, William. 1982.  "The Flat Tax."  <i>New York Times</i> (April 30).
<blockquote>
          Favors flat-rate because existing web of exemptions
          encourages tax evasion; because it would save billions
          now spent on lawyers and accountants to explain tax
          law; and because tax law should not be used to affect
          social policy.
</blockquote><p>
Samuelson, Robert J. 1982.  "Installing Flat Tax Would Prove Messy."  <i>Washington Post</i> (May 18).
<blockquote>
          Favors retention of progressivity because rich receive
          more benefits from government.
</blockquote><p>
Samuelson, Robert J. 1996.  "Call It the Flaky Tax."  <i>Newsweek</i> (January 29), p. 27.
<p>
Schaefer, Rebecca S. 1995.  "Straight Talk About the Flat Tax." 
     Issues and Answers, <i>Citizens for a Sound Economy</i> (May 4).
<p>
Schoeck, Helmut. 1966.  <i>Envy: A Theory of Social Behavior</i>.  New York: Harcourt, Brace & World, pp. 323-330.
<blockquote>
          Discusses progressive taxation as an aspect of envy--
the desire to punish others for their success.
</blockquote><p>
Senate Finance Committee. 1982.  <i>Flat-Rate Tax</i>.  2 parts, 97th Congress, 2nd session.  Washington: U.S. Government Printing
     Office.
<blockquote>
          Most extensive hearings ever held on flat-rate tax. 
          Contains testimony from the U.S. Treasury Department,
          many senators, experts of various kinds, as well as a
          wide number of special interest groups.
</blockquote><p>
Senate Finance Committee. 1995.  <i>Flat Tax Proposals</i>.  Senate Hearing 104-209, 104th Congress, 1st session.  Washington:
     U.S. Government Printing Office.
<blockquote>
          Contains testimony by Alan Auerbach, UC-Berkely; Joel
          Slemrod, University of Michigan; Bruce Bartlett, NCPA;
          Michael Graetz, Yale; Laurence Kotlikoff, Boston
          University; and Alvin Rabushka, Hoover Institution.
</blockquote><p>
Shelton, Judy. 1995. "A Flat Tax for a Strong Dollar." <i>Washington
     Post</i> (September 6).
<blockquote>
          Believes that a flat tax would strengthen the dollar. 
          For a contrary view, see Dunn (1995).
</blockquote><p>
Shlaes, Amity. 1995. "Flat Tax Flap."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i>
     (October 20)
<p>
Simon, William E. 1982.  "What a Flat-Rate Income Tax Would Mean
     to You."  <i>Reader's Digest</i> (November), pp. 122-126.
<blockquote>
          A former Secretary of the Treasury strongly favors a
          flat-rate tax because it would be fairer and because it
          would stimulate economic growth.
</blockquote><p>
Simon, William E. 1995.  "Flat Tax Is Test of GOP's Sincerity." 
    <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (May 24).
<p>
Slemrod, Joel, and Nikki Sorum. 1984.  "The Compliance Cost of the U.S. Individual Income Tax System." <i>National Tax
     Journal</i>, vol. 37, no. 4 (December), pp. 461-474.
<blockquote>
          Estimates the compliance cost of the federal and state
          individual income tax systems at between $17 and $27
          billion in 1982, or 5% to 7% of revenue collected.  See
          also Payne (1993) and Blumental and Slemrod (1992).
</blockquote><p>
Slemrod, Joel, and Shlomo Yitzhaki. 1983.  "On Choosing a Flat-Rate Income Tax System."  <i>National Tax Journal</i>, vol. 36, no.
     1 (March), pp. 31-44.
<blockquote>
          Presents data allowing flat-rate advocates to choose
          among various tax rate and tax base assumptions.
</blockquote><p>
Smith, Dan Throop. 1968.  "High Progressive Tax Rates: Inequality
     and Immorality."  <i>University of Florida Law Review</i>, vol. 20,
     no. 4 (Spring), pp. 451-463.
<blockquote>
          A professor of finance at the Harvard Business School
          argues against high progressive tax rates principally
          on the grounds that they encourage tax evasion and
          undermine compliance with the tax law.
</blockquote><p>
Stokey, Nancy L., and Sergio Rebelo. 1995.  "Growth Effects of Flat-Rate Taxes."  <i>Journal of Political Economy</i>, vol. 103,
     no. 3 (June), pp. 519-550.
<blockquote>
          Finds modest growth effects from tax reform.
</blockquote><p>
Stuart, Charles. 1984.  "Welfare Costs per Dollar of Additional Tax Revenue in the United States."  <i>American Economic
     Review</i>, vol. 74, no. 3 (June), pp. 352-62.
<blockquote>
          Finds that the marginal welfare cost per tax dollar may
          be as high as $1.
</blockquote><p>
Sullivan, Martin. 1995.  <i>Flat Taxes and Consumption Taxes: A Guide to the Debate</i>.  Washington: American Institute of
     Certified Public Accountants.
<p>
Talley, Louis Alan. 1982.  "Estimates of Flat Income Tax Rates Using Various Tax Bases."  <i>Tax Notes </i>(June 21), pp. 952-956.
<blockquote>
          An economist at the Congressional Research Service
          points out that economic effects of flat-rate tax
          depend critically on definition of taxable income
          (i.e., tax base).
</blockquote><p>
Tannenwald, Robert. 1983.  "Redistribution of Wealth in
     Conversion to a Flat Rate Tax."  <i>New England Economic
     Review</i>, Federal Reserve Bank of Boston (January/February),
     pp. 5-17.
<blockquote>
          Because taxes and tax preferences are capitalized in
          the value of assets, any move toward a flat-rate tax
          will have wealth effects.  Finds that middle income
          investors will bear heaviest burden of transition.
</blockquote><p>
Taylor, Robert C. 1986.  "Low Marginal Rates Could Backfire."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (June 10).
<blockquote>
          Opposes tax reform and believes that many deductions
          serve a useful social purpose.
</blockquote><p>
Tax Foundation. 1985.  <i>Flatter Taxes and Fatter Bases</i>. 
     Washington: Tax Foundation.
<p>
Ture, Norman. 1982.  "The Flat Tax Challenge."  <i>Backgrounder</i> No.
     212, The Heritage Foundation (September 21).
<blockquote>
          A former under secretary of the Treasury argues that
          rate structure of the income tax is less important than
          the overall impact of the tax system.  Favors greater
          tax neutrality
</blockquote><p>
Ture, Norman. 1994.  "The Flat Tax: A Guide to Constructive Tax Restructuring." <i> Commonsense</i> (Fall), pp. 35-47.
<p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1984.  <i>Tax Reform for Fairness,
     Simplicity, and Economic Growth: The Treasury Department
     Report to the President</i>, vol. 1, Overview.  Washington: U.S.
     Government Printing Office (November), pp. 21-23.
<blockquote>
          Argues against a pure flat-rate tax on distributional
          grounds.
</blockquote><p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1986.  <i>Report to Congress on an
     Economic Analysis of Gross Income Taxes</i>.  Washington:
     Department of the Treasury, Office of the Secretary, Office
     of Tax Analysis (November).
<blockquote>
          Opposes a flat tax proposal known as a gross receipts
          tax because it would allow no deduction for business
          expenses, thus resulting in "cascading" and sharp
          variations in tax rates from one business to another. 
          See also U.S. General Accounting Office (1989).
</blockquote><p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1992.  <i>Restructuring the U.S. Tax System for the 21st Century: An Option for Fundamental
     Reform</i>.  Washington: U.S. Treasury Department.
<p>
U.S. Treasury Department. 1995. <i>An Analysis of the New Armey-Shelby Flat Tax Proposal</i>.  Washington: U.S. Treasury
     Department, Office of Tax Analysis.
<blockquote>
          Revenue and distributional analysis of one flat tax
          proposal.  Finds that it would be revenue-neutral at a
          20.8% rate.  This report was also published in Tax
          Notes, vol. 70, no. 4 (January 22, 1996), pp. 451-61.
</blockquote><p>
Vedder, Richard K. 1986.  "Tithing for Leviathan: The Case for a
     True Flat-Rate Tax."  In Dwight Lee, ed., <i>Taxation and the
     Deficit Economy: Fiscal Policy and Capital Formation in the
     United States</i>.  San Francisco: Pacific Institute for Public
     Policy, pp. 141-169.
<blockquote>
          A professor of economics at Ohio University favors a
          pure flat-rate tax system.
</blockquote><p>
Vedder, Richard, and Christopher Frenze. 1983.  "Fairness and the
     Flat Rate Tax."  <i>Journal of Contemporary Studies</i>, vol. 6,
     no. 1 (Winter), pp. 45-50.
<blockquote>
          Indicate that Hall-Rabushka proposal would restore the
          tax system to roughly the same level of progressivity
          prevailing when John F. Kennedy was president.
</blockquote><p>
