<html>
<head>
<title>Telecommunications: More Computing than Communications -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h1>Telecommunications: More Computing than Communications</h1>

<b>By <a href="people/director.html#Keyworth">G. A. (Jay) Keyworth, II</a></b>

<P>
The challenge that we are addressing is no less than how to best succeed,
as a nation, in the transition from what Alvin and Heidi Toffler describe
as going from the second wave industrial age to the "third wave" knowledge
age -- a transition in which we are already, irreversibly immersed. The
objectives we emphasize are enhancing economic growth and empowering
individuals.
<P>
Yet, as I delve into the rich media treatment of telecommunications policy
and the information superhighway, I am often left with the impression that
breaking the local access monopoly in voice telephony and adding a few
hundred more cable channels will somehow, inexplicably, lead us to a better
world. The problem is that the metaphor telecommunications is strong in
terms of communications, which only weakly signifies the magnitude of the
issue, but which, in turn, is weak in terms of computing, the term that far
better describes the pathway to those twin objectives -- enhancing economic
growth and empowering individuals.
<P>
From an overarching technology perspective, what we all want to accomplish
is the conversion of today's outmoded, analog communications
infrastructure, designed for voice communications, to a broader-band,
digital one, designed to connect all kinds of computers. Whether labeled
PC's, digital-TV's, digital phones, digital appliances, faxes or whatever,
they are all digital devices whose enabling "brain" is a computer.
<P>
Information is, of course, the item of value, while communications is the
means to move it and computing is the means to make it useful. Taken
together they comprise cyberspace, the environment of the information age.
<P>
Although perhaps powerful in content, this perspective lacks that one
element so essential to human communication -- analogy with things that
comprise real-world experience. But it need not be so. While the world of
ubiquitous digital connectivity is relatively new, with the Internet as its
precursor, the world of pervasive computing is already here, with hackers
as its first-generation of offspring. From the PC revolution we learned a
lot about those two objectives -- economic growth and individual
empowerment -- more than we sometimes realize, and most of it is applicable
directly to how we view telecommunications policy.
<P>
In fact, converting the existing, analog telecommunications infrastructure
to digital is largely an extension of the revolution that began in
computing a generation ago. Manifested in more than one hundred million PCs
in just the United States alone, and having already spread to a third of
our homes, that revolution is now straining at its analog bonds, crying out
to be "connected." To calibrate the term "pervasive," or rather the pace of
that term, in referring to the PC revolution, it is noteworthy that it took
four times longer to reach the same proportion of homes with telephones,
even with the stimulus of mandated universal service.
<P>
The race for leadership in computing, concern over which was largely
responsible in the 1980s for making the word competitiveness part of our
daily lexicon, is, for the moment, over. And we Americans won that race. No
"Fifth Generation Computer Project" in Japan nor "Eureka" program in Europe
affected the outcome, at least not as was intended. Although hotly
contested, we won that race "fair and square," simply by providing the
value customers wanted, and at an affordable price. And not least, we won
by being a nation of people quick to adapt to new technology. As a result,
the U.S. computer industry experienced complete restructuring, capped with
upstart Microsoft's market valuation surpassing IBM's. This kind of
wholesale change is not without disruption, but it did occur without
intervention by government, and few view the change as anything but
beneficial to the nation.
<P>
The computer industry is the first "third wave" segment of our economy, and
we weathered this step of the transition well. If our goal is to create
another with the telecommunications segment, then we need to take heed from
the lessons of the computer industry's success. Nowhere else in today's
world is there a better example of how to enhance economic growth, or to
empower individuals. Yet, at the same time, while the example needs to be
viewed as a model for how digital communications, very much the extension
of computing, can flourish, it also need to be viewed as an equally valid
example of how difficult, and dangerous, it can be to try to predict
progress. Looking for people who even vaguely foresaw what has taken place
in the PC revolution is like looking for Sovietologists who predicted the
collapse of the Soviet Empire. What we can say, however, is that America
did something right.
<P>
At The Progress & Freedom Foundation, we believe America's future success
depends on replicating the success of the American computer industry
throughout the telecommunications and information industries.
<P>
Our strategy to help make this happen is a threefold one: First, it is to
develop, promote and win broad agreement on the principles that should
govern society's telecommunications and information frontier, drawing
heavily on lessons from the successes of the computer industry. Second, it
is to develop and promote a public policy agenda to replace the current
regulatory regime with a lean, clean and effective framework of law and
property rights.
<P>
Third, it is to build a coalition that crosses traditional party and
ideological lines to further our vision.
<P>
The projects that are underway to implement this strategy include keeping
current our existing document "Cyberspace and the American Dream: A Magna
Carta for the Knowledge Age." While based initially on the views of four
authors -- Esther Dyson, George Gilder, Alvin Toffler and myself -- it is a
"living" document, expanding to reflect the views of countless others,
aided by the Internet. It seeks to redefine for the Knowledge Age the
meaning of freedom, structure of self-government, definition of "property,"
nature of "competition," conditions for "cooperation," sense of community
and the nature of "progress."
<P>
Derived from the Magna Carta, we will issue a "Statement of Principles" for
the governance of this new frontier. A series of monographs designed to
enhance public understanding of the task before us, beginning with Alvin
and Heidi Toffler's "Politics of the Third Wave" is underway. We have begun
a project, called "Portal 96," to define a new legal environment for the
electronic frontier. This will be put forth as guidelines to replace the
current regulatory regime with means to enable to the telecommunications
and information industries to replicate the computer industry's success.
<P>
We are preparing, this year, four topical papers, each focused on an issue
that is timely and critical to telecommunications policy. The first will
address reducing barriers to new entrants in providing local access,
something computer industry experience has shown to be even more important
than balancing current contenders. Another will focus on property and
privacy issues, to be done in collaboration with the Center for Democracy
and Technology and the Electronic Frontier Foundation. A third will seek to
place in the context of today those two concepts so central in the history
of telephony -- universal service and common carriage. Finally, the fourth
paper will focus on trends in technology and the implications for
telecommunications policy. The purpose of this more technical paper will be
to point out the need for a fundamental reevaluation of many of the basic
premises that underlay the debate over telecommunications policy. One
example is the potential obsolescence of the idea of spectrum scarcity, in
light of spectrum sharing being enabled by spread-spectrum radio
technology.
<P>
Common to all of these projects will be an effort to expand our reach -- to
gain access to the widest possible range of knowledge, while preserving our
central vision.
<P>
We view our role as one that is more strategic than tactical, where we
emphasize the development of sound principles and deep understanding to
support the writing of laws and regulations. Our objective remains to make
the path that we have, irreversibly, embarked on a better one. We view,
with interest, ongoing legislative efforts to bring current law and
regulations into the "third wave," and we recognize the process to
accomplish that will comprise many steps. While as impatient as any of you,
we're committed to staying the course and to making a difference.
<P>
<i>G. A. (Jay) Keyworth, II is chairman of The Progress & Freedom Foundation.
He delivered these remarks January 31, 1995, at a congressional seminar,
Updating the Communications Act: The Free Market Approach, which was
jointly sponsored by PFF, Citizens for a Sound Economy, The Discovery and
Hudson Institutes, and The Heritage Foundation. Attendees at the seminar
included several members of the U.S. Senate and House, committee and member
staff, press and policy experts.</i>
<p>

<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
