<DOCNO>WT19-B29-104</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA095-001021-B019-283</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/pff/ncp_beyond-block-grants.html 204.71.237.74 19970121223516 text/html 7336
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 22:35:23 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:36:40 GMT
Content-length: 7150
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Beyond Block Grants -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>Beyond Block Grants: Eliminating Federal Funding for Welfare Programs</h2>
</center>
<b>by <a href="people/afellow.html#Muris">Timothy J. Muris</a> [from the Feb. 95 <i>American Civilization</i>]</b>
<p>
Conservatives are at a crossroads. Committed to balancing the budget by
2002, with modest tax cuts and without reducing Social Security and
Defense, they must reform welfare, Medicare and the numerous programs that
comprise non-defense discretionary spending.
<P>
Depending upon how taxpayers react to the tax cuts, to produce balanced
budget, spending must be reduced to between 18 and 19 percent of GDP, the
lowest level since the mid-1960s. Because defense will fall relative to GDP
to its lowest level in decades even with modest dollar increases, 18
percent of GDP will still leave a large federal establishment.
<P>
Even if Congress successfully reduces the recent explosive growth in
welfare, medical care and non-defense discretionary spending, and even if
it dramatically reduces mandates to state and local governments, the
federal government will still be positioned to interfere throughout our
lives.
<P>
We can do better. Along with the spending restraint described above, the
new Congress should end any involvement in programs that can be better run
by the private sector or by state and local governments. In this way,
federal outlays and revenues could be reduced to 15 to 16 percent of GDP.
<P>
Consider welfare. In 1995, federal spending on these programs will be more
than $300 billion, over 4 percent of GDP. At least three reform options are
available. First, rather than a liberal policy emanating from Washington,
we could try a conservative one. But, as political scientist James Q.
Wilson has stated, we simply do not know how to solve the welfare problem.
In fact, there may be one correct solution.
<P>
Second, we could let the states experiment, receiving block grants from
Washington. Today's block grant, however, is tomorrow's mandated program.
The temptation to impose more and more requirements on programs the federal
government once controlled will likely be irresistible.
<P>
Some federalism strategies follow the proposal made by the Reagan
Administration to nationalize Medicaid and send other welfare programs to
the states. The logic of this "swap" has been political, however, not
programmatic. The argument was that the states would agree to take over the
other welfare programs only if they were releaved of the burden of the
fastest growing problem, Medicaid.
<P>
Moreover, Medicaid is a welfare program. The most important qualification
for Medicaid is receipt of other welfare, as more than half of Medicaid
beneficiaries qualify because they receive AFDC or SSI. Medicaid is not
federally administered. Although the federal government provides more than
half of the funds and mandates numerous program details, each state runs a
Medicaid program, with significant differences among them. Thus, in 1992,
Medicaid payments per beneficiary were around $2,000 in some states (e.g.,
California and Alabama) and over $5,000 in others (e.g., Connecticut and
New York).
<P>
Yet the world has changed since November 8, 1994. A majority of governors
are now Republican, particularly in the most populated states. They appear
willing to accept more responsibility, even if given less money from the
federal government, as long as federal mandates are eliminated. A
federalism strategy, including Medicaid, may be possible -- although some
funds will have to be returned to the states.
<P>
A third reform option is available. We could decentralize not only the
administration and rules for welfare, but also the funding. This reform
could be implemented in three stages.
<P>
First, the states would be told now that in the future (say in five years)
federal taxes would be reduced dramatically and the federal government
would no longer have responsibility for welfare, other than investigation
and reporting. Beginning immediately, the federal government would reduce
program growth. Options include capping expenditures for states with high
growth, encouraging managed care in Medicaid and curtailing current
mandates and other provisions that limit state flexibility.
<P>
Second, as an intermediate step, the states would run these programs,
subject to minimal federal requirements, by receiving grants from the
federal government. The grants to the states would be framed to avoid
"gaming." Thus, states that have done a good job of reducing poverty and
controlling costs would not be punished.
<P>
Third, knowing that a massive federal tax cut is coming soon, states would
decide how they would run welfare programs and how much they would need to
raise their taxes to offset the loss of federal dollars. Most states would
undoubtedly increase their taxes by some amount. But the American taxpayer
would receive a net tax cut.
<P>
One reason is that, because the states are unable to print money, they are
barred from running deficits. (Even under a federal balanced budget
amendment to the Constitution, this option would still be available to the
federal government.) Thus, states have more incentive to control spending.
Indeed, governors have already revealed a much greater ability to restrain
costs than have mandates and often duplicative federal bureaucracy.
<P>
The nature of the federal tax cut would be stipulated now, removing the
need for any subsequent vote. But the exact size (e.g., of an
across-the-board reduction in marginal tax rates) would await additional
data. The key variable would be how much taxes could be cut and still
achieve a balanced budget by 2002. The 1995 law would make estimates, based
on the current economic, technical and policy projections, but the exact
percentages of the tax cut would be adjusted automatically (for example, to
reflect the most recent economic assumptions) to take advantage of
intervening experience. In any event, to assure states of an adequate tax
base, a minimum tax cut would be guaranteed.
<P>
This approach could be followed for other federal programs, including
education and the highway system. It would transform American government.
Rather than the federal behemoth that now directs so much of our lives,
while solving so few problems, the states and local governments would have
complete flexibility to address their unique circumstances. Now, too much
government is distant, removed and overly bureaucratic.
<P>
Reducing the federal role will return decision making closer to the people,
who, after all, are still the ultimate sovereigns in this third century of
the American experiment with limited government.
<P>
<i>Timothy J. Muris is an adjunct fellow at PFF and professor at George Mason
University School of Law.</i>
<p>

</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
