<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What You Pay for Gas</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<blockquote>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>What You Pay for a Cocktail<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<hr>
<P>
 After you finished filing your income tax returns this year,
you may have decided that you needed a good drink.  So you may
have driven to your local liquor store to pick up a bottle of
tequila for some margaritas, or a bottle of vodka for a bloody
mary, or a pint of whiskey.
<P>
 What you didn't realize is that in doing so you were primarily
paying taxes again.  That is because <a href="/atr/tax-presentation/boozoped.html">typically 65% of what you
pay</a> for a bottle of distilled spirits goes to the government in
taxes rather than for the liquor.
<P>
 Based on the most recent available data, the typical retail price
of a 750-ml bottle of 80-proof distilled spirits was $9.37.  This
includes a special Federal excise tax on the bottle of $2.16,
accounting for 23% of the total price.
<P>
 In addition, state and local excise taxes on liquor, and sales
taxes, would average another $1.98, or 21% of the total price.
 Together, these Federal, state and local excise and sales taxes
constitute 44% of what you pay for a bottle of liquor.  Consumers
nationwide currently pay almost $7.5 billion per year in such
taxes.
<P>
 But that is not all.  Before the liquor even reaches the store,
the producer, wholesalers, retailers and their employees pay substantial
taxes as well.  These include Federal income taxes, state income
taxes, Federal payroll taxes, unemployment insurance taxes, workmen's
compensation taxes, local property taxes, and any local income
taxes.  For delivery, they must pay gas taxes, tire excise taxes,
truck highway use taxes, and heavy truck excise taxes.  On the
phones, they must pay telephone excise taxes.  About $1.93 of
what you would pay for the typical bottle of liquor described
above would go for these taxes.
<P>
 Consequently, if you pay $9.37 for a typical bottle of distilled
spirits, about $6.07, or 65%, goes to the government in taxes,
rather than for the spirits.  Everything that goes into making,
marketing and distributing spirits is covered by the 35% of the
sales price, or $3.30, remaining after the taxes are paid.
<P>
 Federal, state and local excise and sales taxes are particularly
harsh for lower income workers.  Data from the U.S. Bureau of
Labor Statistics indicates that about 10 times as much of the
income of lower income workers as of higher income workers goes
to paying taxes.
<P>
 But all of the above taxes are unfair to all workers.  In a democracy,
taxes should not be hidden in the prices of products people buy.
 They should be explicit and clear, so that voters can determine
whether they think these taxes are worth what they are getting
from their government.
<P>
 Thomas Jefferson wrote, &quot;Government should not take out
of the mouth of labor the bread that it has earned.&quot;  But
that is exactly what our greedy and overreaching government does
today.  It taxes you on your income when you earn it, and taxes
it again when you spend it, and taxes you over and over again
along the way.  As a result, the average family today actually
pays more in taxes than on food, clothing, and shelter combined.
<P>
 Tax relief for working people is long overdue.  Such tax reduction
would give workers more control over their own incomes and economic
future.  A major tax reduction would also greatly stimulate the
economy, leading to more jobs, higher wages, and expanded economic
opportunity and prosperity.
<P>
<hr>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>by Peter Ferrara, general counsel and chief
economist at Americans for Tax Reform</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>1320 18<SUP>th</SUP> Street N.W., Washington,
DC  20036  (202) 785-0266.</FONT></CENTER>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
