<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What You Pay for Gas</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<blockquote>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>What You Pay for Beer</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>By Peter J. Ferrara<BR>
<hr>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
 Last April, after you finished doing your income taxes and sent
them off to the IRS, you may have needed a drink.  So you may
have driven to the local convenience store to pick up a bottle
of beer.  What you probably didn't realize was <a href="/atr/tax-presentation/beeroped.html">how much you were
paying in taxes</a> again when you bought the beer.
<P>
 If you bought a beer at a standard price of 77 cents a bottle,
then 15 cents, or about 20%, of what you paid, was for state and
Federal sales and excise taxes.  Both state and Federal governments
impose special excise taxes on beer, in addition to standard sales
taxes.  Consumers paid $9.1 billion to the government in 1993,
the last year in which complete data is available, for such sales
and excise taxes on beer alone.
<P>
 But that is only the beginning.  Out of the amount the consumer
pays to the beer producer, the producer must pay Federal income
taxes, state income taxes, Federal payroll taxes, unemployment
insurance taxes, workmen's compensation taxes, state franchise
taxes, local property taxes, and any local income taxes.  For
the delivery truck, the beer company must pay gas taxes, tire
excise taxes, truck highway use taxes, and heavy truck excise
taxes.  On the phones in the beer factory, the producer must pay
telephone excise taxes.  Out of the remaining 62 cents that goes
to the beer producer after the state and Federal sales and excise
taxes, the producer pays 18 cents, or about 25 percent of his
total sales price, for these taxes.
<P>
 Consequently, when you pay 77 cents for a standard bottle of
beer, about 33 cents, or 43% of the total, goes to the government
for all of the above taxes rather than for the beer.  Everything
that goes into making, marketing and distributing the beer is
covered by the 44 cents remaining after taxes are paid.  About
$21 billion of what consumers paid in beer in 1993 actually went
for taxes.
<P>
 Federal, state and local excise and sales taxes are particularly
harsh for lower income workers.  Data from the U.S. Bureau of
Labor Statistics indicates that about 10 times as much of the
income of lower income workers as higher income workers goes to
paying these taxes.
<P>
 But the above taxes are unfair to all workers.  In a democracy,
taxes should not be hidden in the prices of products people buy.
 They should be explicit and clear, so that voters can determine
whether they think those taxes are worth what they are getting
from their government.
<P>
 Thomas Jefferson wrote, &quot;Government should not take out
of the mouth of labor the bread that it has earned.&quot;  But
that is exactly what our greedy and overreaching government does
today.  It taxes you on your income when you earn it, and taxes
it again when you spend it, and taxes you over and over again
along the way.  As a result, the average family today actually
pays more in taxes than on food, clothing, and shelter combined.
<P>
 Tax relief for working people is long overdue.  Such tax reduction
would give workers more control over their own incomes and economic
future.  A major tax reduction would also greatly stimulate the
economy, leading to more jobs, higher wages, and expanded economic
opportunity and prosperity.
<P>
<hr>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2> Peter Ferrara is general counsel and chief
economist at Americans for Tax Reform</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>1320 18<SUP>th</SUP> Street N.W., Washington,
DC  20036  (202) 785-0266.</FONT></CENTER>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
</HTML>
