<HTML>
<TITLE>SERIOUS FLAWS IN THE KINSEY RESEARCH</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">
<P>
<H2>SERIOUS FLAWS IN THE
<BR>KINSEY RESEARCH</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>
Since the publication of <I>Sexual Behavior in the Human Male</I>
(1948) and <I>Sexual Behavior in the Human Female</I> (1953) there
has been much criticism of the findings and methods of Dr. Alfred
Kinsey. 
<P>
The 1990 book <I>Kinsey, Sex and Fraud</I> (Reisman, Eichel, Court
and Muir; Lochinvar-Huntington House) examined the work of Dr.
Kinsey.  The book revealed a number of serious flaws in his research,
including shocking evidence that Kinsey used data from the sexual
abuse of children.
<P>
According to scientific fraud specialist Dr. Walter Stewart of
the National Research Council, evidence of problems in Kinsey's
research is "compelling.... disturbing...and requires investigation."[1]
 Problems include:
<P>
<LI> <B>Sexual Experiments on Children --</B> The Kinsey male report
contains data on sexual activity of 317 children aged 2 months
to 15 years.  These data were either manufactured or these children
were sexually molested by adults in the name of science.  The
data are contained in graph tables which chronicle attempts to
bring children to "orgasm."
<P>
<LI> <B>Sampling Errors --</B> Kinsey's sample was entirely voluntary
and not representative of the U.S. population.  White people were
overrepresented while Blacks and Latinos were underrepresented.
 In addition, college students, college graduates, and white-collar
workers were overrepresented.  Prison inmates comprised 25 percent
of Kinsey's male sample, even though they made up less than one
percent of the total U.S. population at the time.  Among women,
58 percent of Kinsey's sample were unmarried, three times the
actual number at the time.  Religious people were not adequately
represented and since only 10 states were included, the survey
was regionally skewed.
<P>
<LI> <B>Volunteer Error --</B> Psychologist Abraham Maslow raised
this issue by pointing out that sex surveys are skewed toward
the sexually promiscuous and unconventional.  Many people, especially
in the late 1940s and early 1950s, were not willing to talk openly
about their most intimate lives.  Those who did often exaggerated.
 Maslow proved the volunteer error in a test he conducted at Brooklyn
College and concluded that "the whole basis for Kinsey's
statistics was proven to be shaky."[2] 
<P>
Further evidence of Maslow's contention that sex surveys are inherently
slanted is found in a book written by Wardell Pomeroy, one of
Kinsey's co-authors.  Pomeroy writes:

<P>
"As types, those who took the most romantic view of sex were,
understandably, people who were the most religious -- clergymen
and their wives especially.  Those who were bubbling over to tell
us everything they could were usually homosexuals, particularly
when they discovered by our use of homosexual argot that we knew
about the kind of lives they led.  They would almost visibly expand
with relief and eagerness to talk."[3]
<P>
<LI> <B>Intimidation/Coaching of Respondents --</B> Kinsey instructed
his interviewers to goad their subjects into revelations of their
sexual behavior, especially if the results didn't match the interviewer's
assumptions. Wardell Pomeroy admitted that such coaching was quite
common in the Kinsey team's data collection.[4]  These tactics were
particularly effective with prison inmates.  If the inmates did
not provide answers they would have to return to their cells,
thus losing access to the free candy, soft drinks and cigarettes
provided by the Kinsey interviewers.
<P>
When some interviewees said that they did not do a particular
sex act, the interviewer would say: "Yes, I know you have
never done that, but how old were you the <I>first</I> time that
you did it?"[5] 
<P>
Kinsey's team intimidated subjects when they suspected that the
subject was being dishonest.  According to Kinsey, the interviewers
"...should denounce the subject with considerable severity..."[6]
Kinsey admitted that these tactics were highly unusual: "Such
an attack on a dishonest subject is quite contrary to the usual
rules for interviewing, and a procedure which we at first hesitated
to employ in the present study.  We have, however, decided that
it is a necessary technique in dealing with some individuals."[7]
  
<P>
<LI> <B>Ideological Bias --</B> According to Kinsey biographer Paul
Robinson, Kinsey consistently favored nontraditional forms of
sexuality in the way he constructed his books.  Marital intercourse
was "rudely confined to a single chapter in the back of the
book, where it received about one-third the attention devoted
to homosexual relations... a remarkable feat of sexual leveling...the
fundamental categories of his analysis clearly worked to undermine
the traditional sexual order."[8] A 1989 National Academy of
Sciences report explained that Kinsey "attempted to counter
the traditional religious view that sexual virtue was entirely
composed of heterosexual activity...inside the bonds of marriage..."[9]
Kinsey himself summarized the Old Testament's and the Talmud's
injunctions against sexual relations with animals by saying: "The
student of human folkways is inclined to see a considerable body
of superstition in the origins of all such taboos..."[10]
<P>
In addition to Dr. Walter Stewart and Dr. Abraham Maslow, critics
of the Kinsey reports include a committee appointed by the Commission
on Statistical Standards of the American Statistical Association.
 In 1954 the committee reported several statistical flaws and
concluded that "Kinsey should have been more cautious in
boldly drawing highly precise conclusions from their limited sample."[11]
<P>
The 1989 National Academy of Sciences report warned that the sampling
flaws limited "the comparability and appropriateness of the
Kinsey data as a basis for calculating the prevalence of any form
of sexual conduct."[12]
<P>
The Kinsey data are flawed and have been contradicted by subsequent
research.  However, Kinsey's work continues to be widely used
by policy makers and the culture at large in dealing with sexuality.
 The Kinsey data must be discarded.
<P>
<HR>
<CENTER><H3>ENDNOTES</H3></CENTER>
<font size=-1><ol>
<P><li>Dr. Walter Stewart, Letter to the <I>Canadian Medical Journal</I>, Vol. 146, No. 6,
March 15, 1992. 
<P><li>A.H. Maslow, Letter to Dr. Amram Scheinfeld, April 29, 1970, Archives of the History of
American Psychology, University of Akron. Also, see "Volunteer-error in the Kinsey Study,"
<I>Journal of Abnormal and Social Psychology</I>, Vol. 47, No. 2, April 1953. 
<P><li>Wardell B. Pomeroy, <I>Dr. Kinsey and the Institute for Sex Research</I>, Harper &
Row, 1972, <BR>p. 129.
<P><li>Pomeroy, <I>op cit.</I>
<P><li>Alfred C. Kinsey, et al., <I>Sexual Behavior in the Human Male</I>, W.B. Saunders,
Philadelphia, 1948, p. 55.
<P><li>Ibid.
<P><li>Ibid.
<P><li>Paul Robinson, <I>The Modernization of Sex</I>, Harper & Row, 1976, p. 58-59.
<P><li>Charles F. Turner, Heather G. Miller, and Lincoln E. Moses, eds., <I>AIDS: Sexual
Behavior and Intravenous Drug Use</I>, National Research Council, National Academy Press,
1989, p. 86.
<P><li>Kinsey, et al., <I>op cit.</I> p. 669.
<P><li>William G. Cochran, <I>Statistical Problems of the Kinsey Report on Sexual Behavior
in the Human Male</I>, Commission on Statistical Standards of the American Statistical Association, 1954, p. 4.
<P><li>Turner, et al. <I>op cit.</I>, p. 82
</ol></font>

<p>

