<HTML>
<TITLE>CONSISTENT AND CORRECT CONDOM USE?</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">
<P>
<H2>CONSISTENT AND CORRECT
<BR>CONDOM USE?</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) states that
condoms, in order to be effective, must be put on prior to genital
contact, must remain intact and, most importantly, must be used
<I>consistently and correctly</I>.  But while millions of dollars
are spent each year on public education campaigns to promote &quot;consistent
and correct&quot; condom usage -- from pamphlets in public health
clinics to AIDS education classes in schools to the recent CDC
public service announcements on both radio and television -- many
Americans still do not use condoms consistently or correctly.
<P><UL>
  <LI> A 1990 study published in the <I>American Journal of Public
Health</I> found that most adults in the United States who have
multiple sexual partners do not use condoms consistently.  Among
currently sexually active adults studied, 13 percent had had sex
with more than one partner in the year preceding the study, but
only 8 percent of this group had used condoms consistently.  Moreover,
of the 13 percent of adults who had more than one partner, two-thirds
provided data on primary versus secondary partners, but only 23
percent of these respondents reported using a condom every time
with their nonprimary partners.  (B.C. Leigh, M.T. Temple, and
K.F. Trocki, &quot;The Sexual Behavior of U.S. Adults:  Results
from a National Survey,&quot; <I>American Journal of Public Health</I>,
83:1400-1408, 1993.)
<P>
  <LI> The 1988 National Survey of Family Growth found that only
13 percent of the 1,887 never-married, sexually active women aged
15-49 used condoms &quot;consistently.&quot;  It is significant
to note, however, that this survey's definition of &quot;consistent&quot;
use did <I>not</I> mean using a condom for each <I>act</I> of
intercourse, but rather that the woman had used condoms in every
<I>month</I> throughout the reference period.  In addition, only
41 percent of the entire sample of never-married, sexually active
women had <I>ever</I> used a condom.  (L.B. Potter and J.E. Anderson,
&quot;Patterns of Condom Use and Sexual Behavior Among Never-Married
Women,&quot; <I>Sexually Transmitted Diseases</I>, 20:201-218,
1993.)
<P>
  <LI> A 1989 study of patients at a public sexually transmitted
disease (STD) clinic found that consistent condom use is rare,
even among populations at high risk.  Of the 300 patients who
participated in the survey, 51 percent of the men and 64 percent
of the women reported having had an STD in the past, and 47 percent
of all subjects were diagnosed with an STD on the day they were
interviewed.  Forty percent also agreed that their sexual behavior put them at risk of HIV
infection.  However,
only 25 percent of respondents had used a condom at the most recent
intercourse, and only 16 percent of black respondents and 13 percent
of Hispanics reported having used a condom at their last sexual
encounter.  The participants appeared to understand the benefits
of using condoms regularly; however, only 60 percent said they
had used a condom at least once in the previous two months.  (H.S.
Weinstock, et al., &quot;Factors Associated with Condom Use in
a High-Risk Heterosexual Population,&quot; <I>Sexually Transmitted
Diseases</I>, 20:14-20, 1993.)
<P>
  <LI> A 1991 study published in <I>Family Planning Perspectives</I>
found that more than half of all unmarried male participants (60
percent of Hispanics and 54 percent of non-Hispanics) had had
two or more heterosexual partners in the year preceding the survey.
 Among married men, 18 percent of Hispanics and 9 percent of non-Hispanic
whites had had two or more sexual partners.  However, while 51
percent of Hispanic men and 49 percent of non-Hispanic men did
<I>not</I> always use condoms with their secondary partners, theoretically
putting both themselves and their primary partners at risk, only
20 percent of Hispanic men and 9 percent of non-Hispanic men used
condoms with their primary partners.  (B. Van Oss Martin, C.A.
Gomez, and N. Hearst, &quot;Multiple Heterosexual Partners and
Condom Use Among Hispanics and Non-Hispanic Whites,&quot; <I>Family
Planning Perspectives</I>, 25:170-174, 1993.)</UL>

<p>

<center>
