<DOCNO>WT19-B29-187</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA074-000493-B015-50</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/townhall/spotlights/9-18-95/cse.html 204.71.237.74 19970121235534 text/html 14817
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 23:55:56 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 20-Oct-95 14:26:46 GMT
Content-length: 14632
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Citizens for a Sound Economy</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<i>August 9, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>Citizens for a Sound Economy</h2><br>
<h3>Congress and the Coming Budget Standoff: Let The President Blink First <br>
By Paul Beckner and James Gattuso </h3>
</center>
<hr>
<br> 
"Jim. Jim. just settle down. Let's close the place down and see if anybody  
notices." <p>
 
-- President Ronald Reagan to Budget Director Jim Miller <p>
 
In the battle over the federal budget, the stakes are high. The 
congressional majority has made a balanced budget by 2002 the 
centerpiece of its program to rein in the size and scope of the federal  
government. The president has countered with a plan that puts a balanced  
budget further into the future, and -- according to the Congressional  
Budget Office -- will likely still produce deficits indefinitely. It looks like  
the two sides are on a collision course: that Congress will pass draconian  
bills and the president will veto them, causing what many in Washington  
are calling a "train wreck" -- the shutdown of the government. That  
makes good copy, but a collision won't cause the catastrophe that the  
term "train wreck" implies. <p>
 
The battle is now at its midpoint. Phase one ended in June when Congress  
overwhelmingly approved an historic seven-year budget resolution  
mapping the way to a balanced budget by 2002. Phase two -- 
consideration of specific appropriations and authorization legislation -- is  
being fought out in Congress right now, bill by bill. The House of  
Representatives has already passed most of its appropriations measures,  
with mixed results in terms of budget cutting. The Senate is just  
beginning to turn its attention to the subject. <p>
 
While Congress grinds its way through the process, strategists on both  
sides of the budget battle are already turning their thoughts to the  
climactic stage of the conflict -- one that has come to be known in  
Washington as the "Endgame" -- the final push toward adoption or failure  
of legislation which will lead to a balanced budget. This is the stage that  
will determine who wins and who loses, based in large part upon the  
determination, patience and ingenuity of the players. It is also a stage in  
which Congress has substantial advantages -- making the budget battle  
Congress's to lose. <p>
 
<center><h3> War on Two Fronts </center></h3><p>
 
The war over the federal budget is actually being fought on two fronts.  
Each will likely be played out separately during the Endgame. The first is  
the appropriations process. Congress now has 13 appropriations bills  
before it. They cover fiscal 1996 expenditures for everything from the  
legislative branch itself to the Interior Department. The key date here is  
October 1. If an appropriations bill for any agency is not approved by  
Congress and signed by the president by that date, that agency must shut  
down non-essential operations. (More on that later.) <p>
 
The second front involves a reconciliation bill making permanent  
changes in spending programs. The key date is less clear than it is for  
appropriations. In fact, there's nothing that automatically forces action on  
reconciliation. <p>
 
Nevertheless, Congress does have a weapon on hand that it can use to  
force action: the statutory debt ceiling. If Congress does not act to raise  
the legal limit on federal debt (from its current $4.9 trillion!), the  
government would be barred from borrowing more money. This would  
force it to spend no more than it receives in revenue. Tying reconciliation  
to a debt ceiling increase is probably the only way Congress could get a  
presidential signature on a reconciliation bill. <p>
 
Strange as it may seem, no one knows for certain when the current debt  
ceiling will be reached. It depends upon how fast the government spends  
its money and the ingenuity of the Treasury Department in coming up  
with cash from reserves, from under mattresses and the like. Most  
observers, however, expect the crucial date to be reached sometime in  
late October or November. This will be after the start of the new fiscal  
year, but well within Congress's expected legislative calendar. <p>
 
It is these two likely deadlines that will make the Endgame interesting. In  
Washington budget circles, there is increasing talk of a train wreck which  
will occur if neither side blinks. And, as in a game of chicken, the side  
that is more willing to accept a train wreck (or appears to do so) will win. <p>
 
 
<center><h3>The "Train Wreck" </h3></center><p>
 
But just how bad would the train wreck be? What would really happen if  
the government were forced to close down? Some have portrayed the  
potential effects as catastrophic: mail not being delivered, planes crashing  
due to a lack of air traffic controllers, criminals being set free, and so on.  
In reality, however, the effects of a government closedown would be far  
from catastrophic. <p>
 
Let's first look at what happens if appropriations bills are not passed. The  
basic rules here were first laid out in 1980 by President Carter's Attorney  
General, Benjamin Civiletti. Entitlements, ranging from social security  
payments to farm subsidies, could continue to be paid. By definition,  
such programs do not depend upon annual appropriations for their  
funding. In addition, the president holds certain powers that no lack of  
appropriations can take away. For example, according to Civiletti, the  
president could grant pardons regardless of the status of appropriations. <p>
 
Lastly, and perhaps most importantly, the law that governs how  
appropriations are spent -- the rather optimistically titled "Anti-deficiency  
Act" -- specifically allows essential expenditures in cases of imminent  
emergency, to protect lives or property. <p>
 
Because of these various exceptions and exclusions, "closure" of the  
government during past budget crises have involved less than meets the  
eye. Take, for instance, the most recent closure. In 1990, the government  
"closed" for three days over the Columbus Day weekend. There was great  
consternation and an air of emergency, with nightly newsclips of  
disappointed tourists standing in front of a closed Washington  
Monument. <p>
 
But beyond tourism, the effect was limited. According to a later GAO  
report on the incident, few employees were actually sent home, and most  
of these were with the Interior Department (2,826 of the 2,984 sent home  
by the agencies the GAO surveyed). The Defense Department continued  
to operate, the mail was delivered, air traffic control continued to  
function. Even if the "shut-down" had occurred in midweek, the effect  
would not have been cataclysmic. Out of some three million civilian  
federal employees, less than half a million would have been out of action. <p>
 
Even more telling is what agencies said when the GAO asked what the  
adverse effects of a weekday shutdown would be. "Reduced morale" was  
the number one answer, recited by almost all the agencies. The  
Department of Health and Human Services voiced concern about  
"significant anxiety among employees." The IRS was concerned about a  
"loss of public confidence in the agency"! <p>
 
What about a shutdown due to the debt ceiling? Here the rules are  
different: there is no lack of appropriated money, the government just  
can't borrow any more. Without the power to borrow money, the  
government is -- cold turkey -- put on a balanced budget. It can only  
spend what comes in, and no more. While the president's ability to  
unilaterally reduce spending is limited, he presumably could delay many  
discretionary expenditures until the crisis was resolved. The result would  
be a huge cutback on discretionary spending, but spending on  
entitlements and emergency services likely could continue for some time. <p>
 
<center><h3>Who Has the Edge in the Endgame? </h3></center><p>
 
Putting this all together, who will have the advantage in the Endgame?  
Past experience (the government has been shut down four times in the  
last 15 years) isn't of much help. On each occasion, there was a  
tremendous hue and cry from the media, but no clear verdict from the  
public. <p>
 
After the 1990 Columbus Day closure, the Washington Post and ABC  
News commissioned a poll on whom the public blamed. Fifty-seven  
percent blamed the Congress, while only 14 percent fingered President  
Bush. But remember, in 1990, it was the president who was trying to cut  
costs and Congress that was protecting expenditures. <p>
 
Who will the public support this year? At this point it is not certain.  
However, there are several reasons to believe that Congress moves  
toward the Endgame with the upper hand: <p>
 
* Congress has a clear agenda. If anything is clear in American politics 
today, it is that the congressional leadership has more or less set the 
political agenda since last November. It has clearly defined goals, and  
a plan for achieving those goals. President Clinton has rarely broken out  
of a defensive stance during that time. Here is one thing the public will  
respect during any showdown: it's Congress that's trying to do something  
about today's problems, while the president is defending the status quo. It  
will be easy for the Congress to explain what it is doing and why. The  
White House, by contrast, will have some difficulty explaining its  
defense of the old ways. <p>
 
* White House interests are more at risk. Frankly speaking, the Congress 
will have more hostages during a budget showdown. Put another way, if 
there is a train wreck, most of the passengers will be Democrats. The 
reasoning is simple: the basic commodity at risk during any federal shut 
down is federal spending. And, while the Republicans in Congress have 
pet projects of their own they want to protect, the White House has more. 
This is a basic fact that's not going to change. When the government's not 
spending money, the White House will bleed more seriously than the 
budget-cutters in Congress. <p>
 
This basic equation could only be upset if the consequences of a  
temporary shutdown were so cataclysmic as to be unacceptable to  
supporters of either side. But, as discussed above, it seems clear that  
essential services would continue -- especially if the shutdown were due  
to an appropriations stalemate. As a result, the Congress could credibly --  
and responsibly -- take Reagan's advice: let the place close down and see  
if anyone notices. <p>
 
* Congress controls the terms of debate. Under the Constitution, any  
proposed resolution of a budget standoff must originate in Congress.  
While either side may make informal proposals, only Congress can  
originate actual legislation. Thus, at crucial stages, it is Congress, not the  
president, that can better define the debate and frame the choices to be  
made. This can give Congress an important edge. <p>
 
* Congress has a one-house veto. Another advantage Congress has is  
that both the House and Senate must agree to any compromise. No  
concession can go forward as long as either house refuses to give 
consent. Thus, unlike a chain, Congress's negotiating position will be as  
strong as its strongest link. <p>
 
<center><h3>Some Do's and Don'ts </center></h3><p>
 
While important, these advantages are no guarantee of victory for the  
congressional leadership. Their hand may be strong, but winning will  
depend upon how well they play it. Here are some things they should and  
shouldn't do: <p>
 
-- Do tie the reconciliation bill firmly and irrevocably to any increase in  
the debt ceiling. Without such a linkage, Congress loses virtually all  
negotiating power. Over 150 members have already signed a joint letter  
pledging that they would not vote for any stand-alone debt ceiling  
extension. More should be urged to take the pledge. <p>
 
-- Do discuss in detail -- and often -- just what will and won't happen if 
the government shuts down. The president's major weapon will be fear of 
the unknown. A shutdown must be seen and understood by the public as 
a responsible alternative to business-as-usual. Congress must begin this  
process without delay, rather than do it defensively in response to a  
presidential campaign of fear-mongering. <p>
 
-- Do immediately allay fears of damage to trust funds -- especially the  
social security trust fund. Many trust funds rely solely upon purchase of  
federal debt for their interest income. If there is a suspension of federal  
borrowing authority, Congress must make it clear to the public that trust  
funds will be compensated for any loss of interest income. <p>
 
-- Don't assume a stalemate can -- or should -- be resolved in a few days,  
as in the past. Congress must be prepared to settle in for a long siege, 
perhaps involving a shutdown of several weeks. An added bonus for  
Congress: 1995 is not an election year, so there will be no irresistible rush  
to adjourn. <p>
 
-- Don't let pork barrel projects continue to flood the appropriations bills.  
The last thing that Congress needs is to let President Clinton posture as an  
anti-pork warrior. <p>
 
-- Don't underestimate the American public. Despite what will be said 
and written in Washington, the public will in the end support efforts to 
cut spending and reduce the deficit. And if the members of this Congress 
fail to achieve those ends, the public may not give them a second chance. <p>
 
<center><h3>Conclusion </center></h3><p>
 
The budget Endgame may be the most important test which the 104th  
Congress will face. Congress has promised the American people a  
revolution. The question now is whether it can deliver upon that promise.  
If it can, Congress will have paved the way for the most fundamental  
changes in Washington in half a century. But, if it steps up to the edge,  
and then blinks, the public will assume that Washington is still up to  
business-as-usual. The opportunity for real change will have been lost --  
perhaps for another generation. <p>
 
<i>Paul Beckner is President and James Gattuso is Vice President for Policy  
Development at Citizens for a Sound Economy.</i><p>
<a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a>
