<head>
<title>Civil Society, Social Disorder and the Role of Politics in Renewal -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<h2>Civil Society, Social Disorder and the Role of Politics in Renewal</h2>
<b>by Don Eberly</b>
<p>
America is in the midst of deep cultural conflict and accelerating social
decay. It is hard to recall a previous account in American history when we
faced such a "cultural crisis" or "culture wars" -- civil strife, and even
civil war, but not a crisis of culture. Today's conflict goes to
fundamental questions about ultimate reality, the nature of man and the
role of religious belief in a free, well-ordered society. It is
qualitatively different than previous periods of conflict; they occurred
within the framework of American principles, while today the conflict
concerns the principles themselves.
<P>
Growing numbers of people seek an understanding of the nature and roots of
this crisis, guidance on how we can find our way out, and clarification in
particular on the role politics will play in the process of renewal. The
role of politics will not be easily resolved because the conditions we are
now coping with may be unique in American experience.
<P>
How exactly are our current circumstances different? Their chief
characteristic is a crisis of authority and order -- a collapse of the
values and ideals that once animated and restrained Americans, and a
profound weakening of the institutions that sustain a well ordered society.
The result is a lurching toward the nihilistic abyss. Understood this way,
one can begin to appreciate both the importance and the limitations of the
ballot box as a tool for social change.
<P>
To understand how politics and culture intersect and to determine their
relative importance, one must appreciate that although these realms affect
each other, they are different. Culture is about the non-authoritative
realm of values, attitudes and conduct -- the "habits of the heart" which
are lived out by individuals. Politics, at least as we now practice it,
attends to the authoritarian realm of government.
<P>
Many social theorists maintain that, as a general rule, politics more
reflects than shapes culture over the long haul for the simple reason that
politics can be counted upon to be representative. Politicians like to
please and to win elections and few will dare frustrate the expectations
people have of politics, however flawed and exaggerated they may be; most
office seekers will rise (or descend) to the occasion.
<P>
<h2>Comparing The Functions of Politics and Culture</h2>

Perhaps the easiest way to resolve the question of politics versus culture
is to compare those things which can be done through politics, and perhaps
only through politics, to those things which cannot be done predominantly
through politics. Those committed to one strategy to the exclusion of the
other will likely discover that efforts to both reform government and
restore civil society should be pursued on parallel and equally urgent
tracks. The call to politics, as well as the call to shape culture, present
themselves compellingly.
<P>
Consider the task of politics. Without power, one cannot reform the
middle-class entitlements that are bankrupting the country. One cannot
curtail the federal regulatory behemoth or reform overweening welfare
programs without power. One cannot restore a proper respect for liberty and
property to our judiciary without gaining and exercising power. Even when
it comes to the culture, one cannot curb the complete politicization of
society and the use of government to legitimize lifestyles without, to some
degree, confronting power with power -- whether in our schools, courts,
regulatory agencies or social welfare programs.
<P>
So politics is important and honorable work which must be attended to. But
the limitations of politics must also be squarely faced. If you accept that
the gravest danger to the republic's survival is the unraveling of the
social order, you will appreciate just how little can be done through even
the most sweeping electoral gains.
<P>
Legislative strategies, by themselves, are highly limited in reversing teen
pregnancy and illegitimacy, violence, the vulgarity of culture, the
coarsening of manners, the collapse of marriage as a cultural ideal,
individualism and materialism, and the devaluation of fatherhood. Nor can
politics seriously strengthen the pursuit of excellence in business and
education, create social and spiritual vitality, or recover lost character
or meaning. These are social realities, and they are profoundly affected by
the ideals which are prevalent in the culture at any given time. Over the
long haul, you cannot make up in politics what you have failed to achieve
in culture, and you may not be able to reverse the culture by simply
getting the politics right.
<P>
<h2>Social Disorder and Renewal</h2>

Few appreciate just how much degradation has occurred to private
institutions that nourish character and self-restraint (especially the
family), or comprehend the impact of social systems that too happily
embrace pathology as health and mediocrity as merit. For example, tens of
millions of Americans who now occupy positions of leadership in society are
products of an educational system that teaches dogmatic relativism and
compulsive skepticism.
<P>
Doing away with the therapeutic state might do less than imagined to cure
the pathologies upon which it feeds, except over the very long haul. A
return to full Republican control in 1996 would painfully illustrate this
point. As much as it would reverse objectionable policies coming out of
Washington, and even produce some worthwhile reforms, the most remarkable
result might be its minimal impact on the things that can kill a republic.
One should not fail to recall that 12 years of Republican Presidential
control of the policy reins and bully pulpit produced surging economic
growth, renewed national confidence and family values boosterism -- all of
which did nothing to slow the downward slide of culture (the cultural
indicators took their most southward turn during the 1980s).
<P>
This should not supply an excuse for giving up on politics, but neither
should it supply a mandate for immodesty in our political expectations. The
crisis in America is certainly a crisis of overloaded, intrusive and
increasingly bankrupt democratic institutions, but even more so it is the
attendant collapse of the institutions of civil society. Our goal should be
to get government to do well those things which it alone must do, and
otherwise to develop strategies to shore up civil society.
<P>
The latter will not be done through a preoccupation with legislative
strategies; indeed, in a nation starving for social order, the wrong form
of politics can forestall badly needed social movements and individual
reforms. Government is more capable of tearing down than building up civil
society for the simple reason that civil society does not find its origins
in the authoritarian realm. Order must be restored through other means:
religious revival; social reformation; new social sanctions against
deviance; a renaissance in private character-shaping charity; reviving
fatherhood as a dignified institution; restoring citizenship to its fuller
dimensions; and, renewing a commitment among leaders across all sectors of
society, not just politics, to the First Things.
<P>
<h2>The Politics-Culture Dichotomy</h2>

Here is where the difference, and sometimes incompatibility, of political
and cultural movements arise. The primary purpose of political movements is
often to tear down one's opponent in order to govern; it is to exploit
public issues in order to advance one's partisan, personal or institutional
interests, not necessarily to solve them. The purpose of cultural movements
is to build up a new vision for the good society, embracing all citizens
regardless of politics; it is about changing people and strengthening civil
society, not just directing the affairs of government.
<P>
The primary use of politics in a nation experiencing social disorder is to
revert to a more classical notion in which politics is used to call the
nation to consider the higher ends of life and join in building the good
society. The statesman would seek to reverse the collapse of our governing
consensus, and confront the dangers of internal disorder and fragmentation.
This is a different task than leading a nation through the crisis of war or
economic collapse in which the leader's arsenal consists of military or
policy tools. Moreover, victory or defeat would not be measured in
conventional terms of elections or military surrenders. The work of the
statesman today must be seeking a cure for cultural cancer and reviving
what James Davison Hunter calls "substantive democracy," not simply leading
a holy war against the infidels.
<P>
The unfolding crisis will certainly attract demagogues, but it will take a
statesman of the stature of Lincoln to solve. The tragedy is that most
leaders today, even if they understand the problem, only end up
trivializing and exploiting the issues. There are few persons today who can
simultaneously practice politics effectively and still manage to advance
the things which are not of politics: virtue, character and culture.
<P>
If the problem is deeper than politics, the statesman must not simply be
preoccupied with annihilating political enemies, but equally preoccupied
with strategies for renewal that transcend politics to even include
political opponents. If you believe, as I do, that the nation is nearing
emergency conditions, then indeed the luxury of turning every public
concern into an opportunity for ideological or partisan advancement, on the
theory that political victory equals social salvation, is a luxury America
can no longer afford.
<P>
<h2>Rome and America: From Virtue to Vice, Democracy to Despotism</h2>

The social crisis of America will not be reversed by simply reforming
politics. When ancient Rome slid from a shining city into a darkened
jungle, it was because the people abandoned virtue for decadence. Just as
sure as virtue produced prosperity, the plunge into decadence eventually
destroyed it. Society celebrated deviance as a symbol of liberation from
religious constraints, more and more people substituted leisure for work
and lived off the state, and the record of government policy was to simply
accommodate the "changing values."
<P>
This social disintegration occurred within an economic, governmental and
legal apparatus that was one of the most advanced in human history. No law
and order government, no well conceived legal system and no wealth
enhancing economic structure could prevent the disintegration from within
of a once proud and virtuous society. The lesson of ancient Rome for modern
America is that the forces of cultural nihilism do not stop to pay their
respects to democratic capitalism; our disintegration is of a similar kind
-- it is social.
<P>
Then, as now, the preoccupation of the leadership class was with legal and
economic structures. But no amount of attention to the power plant
prevented the lights from steadily going dim. Then, as now, the leadership
class faced the crisis by simply doing what they knew to do, only trying
harder. Social disorder drove society inexorably toward chaos. Politics was
characterized by endless and pointless polemics that descended unavoidably
into bitter and eventually violent recriminations. This was a society,
completely politicized, whose warring ideologues insisted they could turn
the lights back on if only they got control of the power plant. And it is
this reality, as much as the cultural disintegration in whose name the
fight is fought, that represents the arrival of barbarians at the city
gate. A politics that raises hopes unrealistically high only nourishes the
brutish beast of frustrated expectations, leaving the people even hungrier
for destructive revolutionary change.
<P>
<h2>A Politics of Honesty</h2>

As C.S. Lewis said, civilization is a rarity, "attained with difficulty and
easily lost." Political movements which fail to appreciate the fragility of
society can drive it toward the abyss. To simply win politically does not
mean civil society will necessarily be recovered.
<P>
What we need is a politics based upon principle, honesty, and telling the
truth. Honesty admits the limitations of politics to treat the deepest
roots of our moral and social crisis. A well articulated politics of
honesty may reap dividends in an ideologically exhausted land. Few have
grasped the importance of what Peter Drucker meant when he predicted the
end of the notion of "salvation by state." It is the collapsing of
confidence in the business of the state and the politics that feeds our
current obsession with governmentalism.
<P>
There is a mentality among some political activists of various stripes that
we may need to burn the village down in order to rebuild it. The problem
is, the village these well meaning people have in mind rebuilding would
probably never reemerge in a society that has substituted revolutionary
expectations for the cultivation of virtue and self-governance. Do not
expect stronger civil institutions to magically reappear. Ideological zeal
then, in a disordered society, may be more the disease than the cure.
<P>
<h2>Dividing the Labor of Politics and Culture into Three Zones</h2>

How, then does one organize the work of politics and the work of culture?
Consider three zones, each depicting a function that is important and
complimentary if not always compatible. One is centralized partisan
politics. The closer one comes to Washington, the more one is likely to
practice this form of politics and to be uncomfortable with the analysis
set forth here because it appears to represent a distraction from the
urgent work of government. For diehard politicos, the work of culture
represents a possible diminution of political effort -- politics versus
culture is seen as a zero sum game.
<P>
Those who occupy this first zone indeed are engaged in critical work,
particularly ensuring government "does no harm." And it entails challenging
Americans to do things that only they can do -- strengthening citizenship,
rebuilding moral communities and returning to virtue and mutual respect.
<P>
The second zone is decentralized politics -- less partisan and ideological,
more focused on local government. It involves expanding beyond ideological
constituencies. Alvin and Heidi Toffler predicted that we are moving beyond
"mass movements," "mass politics," "mass parties" and "mass media." Mass
movement politics, which relies on a high degree of cohesion and
conformity, does not fit well in this more fragmented and diffused
political environment. Politics will be driven more and more from the
bottom, and the closer the issue is to home the less people will care to be
identified with national movements.
<P>
The final zone is the cultural-civic realm, a realm which almost requires
that one's ideological commitments be placed in neutral, since the object
of this work is not winning legislative battles but finding solutions
through the community. Some of the most creative work in the coming decades
will be done outside of politics, and this should be embraced as equally
valuable to the cause of renewing America. One might say the work of
civic-cultural renewal involves regeneration, whereas the work of
government should be guided simply by the Hippocratic oath -- do no harm.
<P>
The greatest political movements of the twentieth century achieved their
goals not primarily through legislation, but by affecting the thinking and
attitudes of Americans. The sexual revolution, feminism, the civil rights
movements and environmentalism deeply affected how Americans think about
sex, women, minorities and the environment as much as they changed the
legal system.
<P>
As Lincoln said: "He who moulds public opinion goes deeper than he who
shapes statutes." Still, those who would espouse a "culture over politics"
strategy should accept that a good part of cultural renewal will not be
possible without power, whether applied in government or in confronting the
cultural deconstructionists who have lodged themselves in positions of
power on campuses, the newsrooms and other power centers in the private
sector.
<P>
Those who espouse a "politics over culture" strategy, who believe that the
answer to crime, family collapse and ethical corruption is to become a
Republican should boldly say that, but they should also tell the rest of
the story: politics cannot deliver all the goods. They should use political
platforms to explain that the kind of dynamic cultural/moral/spiritual
renewal the nation now needs will not likely emanate from political action
alone.
<P>
<h2>Finding a Framework for Citizenship and Civic Republicanism</h2>

How then can one use politics, both to reform government and to enlist
Americans in the cause of cultural renewal? We will be aided by an
understanding of an older, fuller notion of citizenship along with reviving
the great American tradition and language of shared American values called
civic republicanism.
<P>
The notion of citizenship is a term that connects the individual to the
totality of public life: the political and the cultural are integrated. The
term certainly embraces democratic duty, i.e., voting and organizing, but
also includes social sympathy, volunteerism, community renewal, civic
participation, and the full range of social responsibilities. Citizens do
more than participate in elections: they organize their communities against
crime; develop strategies against teen pregnancy; volunteer at local soup
kitchens; take their local parks back from drunks; join the PTA; and, pray
for their country at churches and synagogues.
<P>
Civic republicanism offers a framework for transcending religious and
ideological factionalism by reviving a language that is neither secular nor
sectarian. It is a language of social fraternity, strengthened
neighborhoods and a well moderated pluralism of shared values without the
normal linkage to governmentalism. Civic republicanism places the focus of
concern on strengthening the institutions of civil society -- family,
neighborhood, church and synagogue, and voluntary associations. In other
words, the focal point is community, not the central, homogenizing and
totalizing entities (such as national politics and the entertainment/media
culture) that remain so alluring. Indeed, it is local communities that
represent a bulwark against the encroachments of the central state.
<P>
This approach should not be confused with the traditional politics of
limited government, which is based upon the debatable assumption that the
private sector will thrive again in government's absence. This alternative
framework offers a bold call to social reformation; it seeks to mobilize
citizens and leaders from all sectors of society; and, it unashamedly calls
for a return to the American Creed of responsibility, self-governance,
character and community. We must start by appreciating what civil
institutions do -- they habituate (J. Q. Wilson's term) individuals to
restrain themselves and respect others. This approach also acknowledges
that the government as we know it is as much the effect as the cause of
declining civil society.
<P>
Comprehensive reform of government is called for in the form of
decentralization and the wholesale elimination of wasteful, duplicative
programs. However, while demonizing government is good politics, it will
not, by itself, restore a civil and humane society. Indeed, the swift and
indiscriminate elimination of federal poverty programs, absent a
simultaneous, well-orchestrated campaign for community renewal, may only
drive some communities, particularly our cities, closer to state of nature.
<P>
Americans are looking for a new vision for empowerment and civic renewal
that is both political and cultural in impact. Michael Novak, who has long
articulated this vision of empowerment, said: "The American political party
that best gives life and breath and amplitude to civil society will not
only thrive in the twenty-first century. It will win popular gratitude and
it will govern."
<P>
A new paradigm for renewal is emerging, and it presents huge possibilities
for reversing America's social regression. Its arrival will be aided
greatly by a clear-headed understanding of the relative value of political
versus social change and how the work of politics and culture can be
integrated.
<P>
Realizing the possibilities will not be easy. Though deeply American, this
ascendant paradigm has fallen out of practice and even memory, and is thus
hard to visualize. Plus, its rebirth may very well be aborted by a
deepening cultural and ideological polarization. Moreover, the traditional
cycle of American renewal will have to work its way through a different
social and political topography this time. America is different today,
radically so: changes in structure and demographics; the information
overload resulting from the technology revolution; globalization; the rise
of racial and ethnic identity and the decline in common culture; and, the
weakening of nation state as an organizing construct all make the task so
much more complex.
<P>
In the end, acknowledging that the crisis is social presents both the bad
and good news. The good news is that periodic self-renewal, just like
today, is usually preceded by a broad acceptance that things are bad, and
beyond conventional solutions. If there is such a thing as American
Exceptionalism, its chief ingredient is this unique capacity to renew
itself.
<P>
Great opportunities await us. Millions are looking into the abyss of
nihilism and don't like what they see. They are confused about what to do.
Is it politics and power, or is it culture and community. It is both: each
embraced and used to promote the restoration of a civil and humane society.
<P>


<i>Don Eberly is president of The Commonwealth Foundation of Harrisburg,
Pennsylvania.</i>
<p>

<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
