<html>
<title>SCHOOL DAYS, SEX DAZE</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>SCHOOL DAYS, SEX DAZE</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Robert H. Knight</i></center>
<p>
As little Johnny or Joanie adjust to the reality of another school
year, they might find that it is a little bit tough to concentrate
on academics.
<p>
How, indeed, can children keep their mind on arithmetic when they
are exposed to sex in a big way?  From kindergarten on, many children
are learning the ABC's of sexuality, taught in a &quot;morally
neutral&quot; manner in state-mandated programs.
<p>
Despite two decades of documented failure to reduce the ravages
of teen sex, the effort to sexualize children at younger and younger
ages continues apace.  The rationale used to be &quot;sexual health&quot;
or reproductive safety.  Now, the same bad medicine is being peddled
under the rubric of  &quot;AIDS prevention.&quot;  Each year,
it gets earlier, more graphic, and increasingly incorporates &quot;alternative
lifestyles.&quot;
<p>
Parents are being cut out of the act.  In Falmouth, Massachusetts,
a court ruled recently that schools could pass out condoms even
if parents object.  In school libraries, books like <i>Heather
Has Two Mommies</i> are taking their place alongside Dr. Seuss.
 Parents who object are called &quot;bigots&quot; and &quot;religious
fanatics.&quot;
<p>
Why did much of America's educational establishment buy into the
notion that children should be taught about sex years before puberty?
 Part of the answer can be found in Indiana, at the world-famous
Kinsey Institute.  It was here, in the late 1940s, that Dr. Alfred
C. Kinsey published his famous Kinsey Report, formally known as
<i>Sexual Behavior in the Human Male</i>.  As revealed by Dr.
Judith A. Reisman in a 1981 paper, and further explored in the
1990 book <i>Kinsey, Sex and Fraud</i>, by Dr. Reisman, Edward
W. Eichel, Dr. J. Gordon Muir and Dr. John H. Court, the Kinsey
material contains a chapter on child sexuality that has been the
basis for the view that children are sexually viable at all ages.
<p>
Graph tables (Tables 31 and 34) report data that can have been
gathered only during the sexual molestation of children from two months
to 15 years of age with climaxes recorded by the use of a &quot;second
hand or stopwatch.&quot;
<p>
In one instance, a four-year-old boy was said to have had 26 &quot;orgasms&quot;
in a 24-hour period.  Because molestation of children is illegal,
the Kinsey studies have been the only data on child sexuality
to achieve wide usage.
<p>
Efforts to open the Kinsey files on the child sex experiments
have been rebuffed by current director John Bancroft as well as
his predecessors.  How did Kinsey get this data?  Where did the
children come from?  Are their identities known today?  Who committed
these acts?  These questions remain unanswered.
<p>
Incredibly, even as the rest of the Kinsey Report became the touchstone
of the sexual revolution, the child data has largely been ignored
by the popular culture -- even though it may have had the most
far-reaching effect on academic views about child sexuality.
<p>
The Kinsey view of child sexuality, although based on criminal
abuse of children, has been promoted for years through major sex
education institutions to which Kinsey's disciples migrated. 
Taxpayers are being forced to fund the Kinseyan agenda through
federal grants to the Sex Information and Education Council of
the United States (SIECUS), which was founded by Kinsey colleagues
and disciples.
<p>
SIECUS co-founder Mary Calderone, former medical director of Planned
Parenthood, has said that the SIECUS mission is to educate society
&quot;very broadly and deeply with awareness of the vital importance
of infant and childhood sexuality.&quot;
<p>
Current SIECUS President Debra Haffner has envisioned a &quot;national
petting project,&quot; in which youngsters are taught to strip
and masturbate each other and to engage in &quot;outercourse&quot;
as a way to forestall intercourse.  This view was echoed by former
Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders, who on the advice of SIECUS counselors,
advocated teaching children how to masturbate.
<p>
But educators are not the only intended carrier of the Kinsey
gospel.  In its blueprint document, <I>Sex Education 2000</I>,
SIECUS &quot;calls on the national media to present sexuality
as a positive aspect of the total human experience <I>at all stages
of the life cycle</I>&quot; (emphasis mine).
<p>
Apparently, Calvin Klein got the message, judging by its recent
kiddie-porn style ad campaign for jeans.  The print and TV ads
show young teens in various states of undress with camera angles
and settings that evoke classic themes of child pornography. 
Klein's defense of the lascivious commercials was vintage Kinsey/SIECUS.
In a  full-page ad in <I>The New York Times</I>, the designer
called the campaign &quot;positive&quot; because the ads convey
the idea that &quot;young people today...have a real strength
of character and independence.&quot;  Translated: You are great,
kid.  Only <I>you</I> know what is right.  Now strip for the camera.
Then get back to class.  You've still got a lot to learn.
<p>
It is time for the Kinsey Institute to open its file and solve
a 50-year-old cover-up that is still having a profound effect
on our culture.  And it is time to curb the ongoing crusade in
education and popular culture to rob our children of an irreplaceable
treasure -- their innocence.
<p>
-- 9/26/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Robert H. Knight, Director of Cultural Studies at the Washington,
D.C.-based Family Research Council, wrote and directed a new video
documentary about Alfred Kinsey, <b>The Children of Table 34.
</b></i>

<p>

