<head>
<title>School Choice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<i><b>March 1995</i></b>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<center>
<h2>Choice in Action:</h2><br>
<h3>What's Working Around the Country</h3><p>
<i>The Center for Education Reform</i> 
</center>
<hr>
<br> 
With the increasing demand for better schools, dozens of states and 
communities are providing more options to families. By doing so, they 
are not only improving the condition of education for those children, but 
having a dramatic impact on how schools operate in their communities.  
Armed with the evidence presented below, lawmakers in each of a dozen 
states will soon give serious consideration to launching and expanding 
upon the school choices provided to their citizens.<p> 
Milwaukee, Wisconsin, implemented the nation's first pilot school 
choice plan in September, 1990.  The program provides up to 1,500 low-
income children with a grant of half the Milwaukee per-pupil expenditure 
($3,200 for the 1994-95 school year) to attend the private, non-sectarian 
school of their choice.   In 1990, 341 Milwaukee children used grants at 
six private schools.  Today, the initiative is enabling 830 students to 
attend one of thirteen participating private schools -- with hundreds of 
children on waiting lists. Participation in the Milwaukee program has 
been limited because of restrictions on the schools that may participate.  
However, Wisconsin Governor Tommy Thompson has pledged to expand 
the program to allow all private schools, including sectarian schools, to 
participate, and has included funds for such an expansion in his 1995 
budget.<p> 
Evaluations for the Milwaukee program show that choice students are 
ten times more likely than their public school counterparts to stay in their 
choice school through the year, and 50% more likely to be there the next 
year, despite the fact that choice students are more often from single-
parent homes on welfare, closest to the poverty line.  The choice program 
has resulted in high levels of parent and student satisfaction, increased 
parental involvement in their children's education and with the schools, 
and improved discipline and attendance.(1)<p> 
In September, 1993, the Puerto Rico legislature passed the first state-
wide full school choice law, providing $1,500 grants for children from 
low-income families to attend a private school or a public school of their 
choice.  In 1993, 1,596 students participated in the program; in 1994 that 
number increased more than ten-fold, to 16,899.  The vast majority of 
those students -- 88% -- chose to transfer from a private or a public 
school into another public school; the rest opted for a private school.  In 
1994, the Puerto Rico Supreme Court declared the section of the program 
extending to private schools unconstitutional, but the decision did not 
affect the nearly 15,000 children using the public school choice option.  
The ruling also did not affect the reality that so many children, once 
empowered, chose to go to a different school, whether public or private.<p> 
The earliest evidence of choice working came from New York's East 
Harlem school district.  In 1974, the school district gave parents the right 
to choose among diverse schools-within-schools created by teachers.  The 
resulting competition increased education quality: graduation rates shot 
up from less than 50 percent to more than 90 percent; the district, which 
ranked last of New York City's 32 districts in reading scores, climbed to 
16th; community morale soared as the choice program brought parents 
and teachers together to work on behalf of their children; and the plan 
continues to attract students from districts across New York City, creating 
voluntary desegregation.  The students are strong choice proponents, and 
say it gives them a sense of ownership and pride in their schools that they 
did not have before.<p> 
In 1993, when another three New York City districts opened up schools 
to choice, a summer school fair drew over 1,000 parents eager to learn 
about their options.  Choice for the city's 80,000 high schoolers is 
available through the wide array of magnet schools that operate 
throughout New York City, many on a selective admissions basis.  And 
the trend has spread to other urban districts demanding a better system.  
In Boston, Massachusetts (enrollment 60,000), Indianapolis, Indiana 
(enrollment 47,000), and Detroit, Michigan (enrollment 50,000), parents 
must choose which school their child will attend.  In Boston, 57% of 
students now choose to go to schools other than those to which they were 
assigned.<p> 
The competition among schools trying to attract students -- even when 
limited to the public sector -- has forced schools to be more informative 
to parents and to offer a better product.  When open enrollment was 
introduced in Los Angeles in the Fall of 1993, with 22,000 seats open in 
the district, schools aggressively marketed their wares via cable television 
and local newspapers to attract parents and show they could offer their 
children something better.  And when schools in a choice state are faced 
with dipping enrollments, they are forced to raise their own standards.  
When high school students began to use Minnesota's post-secondary 
enrollment option to earn their high school credits on college campuses, 
high schools responded by quadrupling the number of advance placement 
courses they offered in order to attract students, and their funding, back 
to the high schools.<p> 
In fact, in Minnesota 15% of the state's 750,000 public school students 
participate in the various choice programs available throughout the state -
- using their school choice to get the education best tailored to their 
needs.  In 1987, the program's first year, over 2,000 dropouts enrolled in 
alternative schools through the new choice plan; by 1993, 14,000 
dropouts were opting back into schools through Minnesota's various 
"second chance" programs.  Recently, the first religiously affiliated high 
school joined the ranks of private high schools in the state contracted by 
districts to educate at-risk students that the public school system can no 
longer handle. Through a similar program in Arizona, districts every year 
send about 2,000 children who aren't benefiting from their district school 
to private schools more suited to their needs.<p> 
Meanwhile, private scholarship programs are working in more than 20 
cities to enable over 8,500 children from disadvantaged families to attend 
the school of their choice.  And nearly 10,000 children are on waiting 
lists. The infusion of private enterprise into the choice equation not only 
enhances the options available to children, particularly the most 
underprivileged, but also imposes a greater challenge to existing public 
schools to respond more directly to children's' needs.<p> 
Throughout the country, dozens of public and private sector programs 
are expanding the choices available to families, and, in so doing, are 
having a positive effect on the quality of education all children receive.<p> 
<i>1 Peterson, Paul E.  A Critique of the Witte Evaluation of Milwaukee' 
School Choice Program, (Cambridge, MA:  Harvard University, February 
1995.) </i><p>
<i>The Center for Education Reform can provide you with more information 
on these or other program.</i><p>  
